<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Budget for 2000-2001 Shows Big Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Finance Minister Shah AMS
Kibria Thursday placed a national budget of 8.5 billion U.S.
dollars for fiscal 2000-2001, showing an overall deficit of 3.7
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
He estimated the revenue income at 4.8 billion dollars, 13.3
percent higher than the revised income for the outgoing fiscal
1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
The non-development expenditure was estimated at 3.9 billion
dollars, up from the revised estimate of 3.68 billion dollars this
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister proposed to meet the big deficit, which is
equal to 5.9 percent of gross domestic product, from foreign
grants and loans of 1.88 billion dollars, domestic sources of 1.1
billion dollars and from bank borrowings of 0.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Defending the much talked excess borrowings by the government
from the banking sector, Kibria said the experience of financial
management in Bangladesh during the last two years suggests that
harmful effects of bank borrowing are limited.
</P>
<P>
"There is no direct correlation between government borrowing
and inflation in Bangladesh. On the contrary, inflation rate in
Bangladesh has been continuously falling during last ten months
despite a surge in government borrowing," he said in the
parliament Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Proposing 3.5 billion dollars for the Annual Development
Program (ADP for fiscal 2000-2001, which is 13 percent higher than
the current year's revised size, Kibria said more than half of the
resources would be provided by domestic sources while 49.8 percent
from foreign sources.
</P>
<P>
The allocation for rural development has increased by 250
percent over the last five years. In 1995-96, the allocation for
the sector was 145 million dollars while 364 million dollars has
been proposed under the ADP for the coming fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Allocation of 1.1 billion dollars for the education sector has
been proposed in the new budget for fiscal 2000-2001 marking it
the highest allocated sector both in terms of revenue and
development expenditure.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth budget of the Awami League (People's League)
government led by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina since it assumed
power in the general elections held in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The entire opposition continued their abstention from the house
as the finance minister placed the budget.  
</P>
</TEXT>
