<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chittagong Trade Unions Agree to Building Second Terminal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Work for building a second container
terminal at Chittagong Port, the largest port in Bangladesh, will
start soon as trade unions withdrew their objection to foreign
involvement in the venture, the United News of Bangladesh Thursday
quoted official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has offered an investment of 7.
37 billion taka (142 million U.S. dollars) in the New Mooring
Container Terminal, which was vehemently protested against by the
port workers, opposition parties, and even by the Chittagong city
mayor who belongs to the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
The mayor had described the government's decision on the
foreign involvement in the second container terminal as a threat
to national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Main trade unions, namely Bandar Sramik Dal (Port Workers'
Organization), Bandar Sramik League (Port Workers' League), Islami
Sramik Sangha (Islami Workers' Association) and Bandar Sramik
Union (Port Workers' Union), in a body had opposed the ADB
involvement in the project, fearing that the donor would grab port
business.
</P>
<P>
However, these labor organizations, except Bandar Sramik Union,
in a meeting last week changed their minds and gave their consent
to the implementation of the scheme with condition.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Chittagong Port Authority, they pleaded that
it should be a joint venture with the management control in the
hands of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong port is not capable of coping with the bulk
import and export cargo. Official sources said the proposed
terminal will reduce container jams and enhance operational
capacity of the port.
</P>
<P>
It will also bring more dynamism into the country's export and
import business, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
