<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Nuke Capability "Modest:" Foreign Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Thursday said its
nuclear capability is "modest" and solely aimed at deterring
aggression.
</P>
<P>
This was stated in a Foreign Office statement issued here in
reaction to a report of the National Broadcasting Company (NBC of
America which claimed that, as compared to India, Pakistan
possesses far larger nuclear capability and arsenal and better
delivery systems.
</P>
<P>
The claim was "removed from reality and appears to be motivated,
" said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"This is an extraordinary assertion in view of the fact that in
comparison with a few Pakistani nuclear facilities, India has a
vast nuclear program comprising dozens of nuclear installations
outside international safeguards, which have been operating to
produce fissile materials over decades," it added.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the NBC report also falsely surmised
that Pakistan's program relied on generous outside assistance,
while crediting India's nuclear arsenal to indigenous effort.
</P>
<P>
"It ignores the fact that a large part of the Indian nuclear
facilities is of Western origin in addition to a vast number of
Indian nuclear and missile specialists who had been trained in the
West. On the other hand, Pakistan has been constantly subjected to
economic and technological sanctions and its program kept under
close scrutiny."
</P>
<P>
The report carried "dangerous implications" as it "tends to
justify the ambitious Indian program for nuclear and conventional
build-up," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating that Pakistan will continue to follow a policy of
restraint and responsibility on nuclear issues, it said, "Pakistan
's nuclear capability is modest and solely aimed at deterring
aggression. We are opposed to an arms race and will maintain
nuclear deterrence at the minimum credible level."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
