<HEADLINE> Central Asian States Push Further Regional Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Government leaders from Central
Asian countries met Thursday at the Kazak capital Astana and
approved a series of documents guiding economic integration in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan and Uzbekistan from the
Central Asian Economic Community agreed on measures to unify their
customs rules and discussed the sharing of water resources and
electric power and other issues at the meeting viewed as an
important step in reinforcing their partnership.
</P>
<P>
Government leaders of the countries also called for
strengthened cooperation in combating illegal financial dealings
and other economic crimes, while reiterating the role of a
quadrilateral agreement signed last April on joint fight against
terrorism, extremism and organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Kazak Prime Minister Kasymzhomart Tokayev told a press
conference after the meeting that terrorism and drug trafficking
have become the main problems facing the region.
</P>
<P>
The Central Asian Economic Community was launched in March 1998
when Tajikistan joined it. Its predecessor is the Central Asian
Union founded in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Euro 2000 Ticket Sales Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said on
Thursday it had approved Euro 2000's ticket sales policy.
</P>
<P>
The championships kicks off in Brussels on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement comes the day after Amsterdam-based agency
Cupido Tickets formally complained to the Commission and Dutch
competition authorities that the tournament's ticketing
arrangements violated EU law.
</P>
<P>
The Commission said ticketing policy was in line with the bloc'
s competition rules and respected the EU's principle of non-
discrimination between nationalities.
</P>
<P>
The Commission said its statement was intended to reassure fans
following the fiasco of the 1998 World Cup, after which the EU
executive fined the French organisers a symbolic 1,000 euros (959.
7 U.S. dollars) for favoring French residents in ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
"By contrast, the arrangements agreed for the Euro 2000
tournament appear to have given European consumers a genuine
possibility to obtain tickets for all matches under fair and non-
discriminatory conditions," the Commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Spokeswoman Amelia Torres said the Commission had received a
complaint against the Euro 2000 ticketing policies and had taken
it into account in deciding the system was fair.
</P>
<P>
Euro 2000 said on Wednesday it had sold 97 percent of the
available 1.2 million tickets, with 39 percent going to the
general public and 36 percent to the national football
associations of the participating teams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
