<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Promises Continued Commitment to S. Leone Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Two warships and about 200 British
soldiers will remain in Sierra Leone to show Britain's commitment
to the country's fragile peace after the bulk of the British
troops leave on schedule next week, said British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Freetown quoted Cook as saying that
the British frigate, HMS Argyll, and a support vessel, Sir
Percivale, would serve as "visible, clear evidence of Britain's
commitment."
</P>
<P>
Cook is paying a visit to Sierra Leone. During his meeting with
Sierra Leonean President Ahmad Kabbah at the heavily guarded state
house in the capital, Cook said that a team of about 200 British
soldiers would remain to train Sierra Leone's newly recruited
national army.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Britain sent a naval task force and more than 1,000
troops to the West African nation to help withdraw British
nationals and beef up the United Nations' operations, which were
nearly paralyzed by the rebels' sudden attacks and hostage-taking.
</P>
<P>
"British troops are withdrawing on schedule because they have
carried out their objective which was to make sure that British
nationals could get out safely and also that the U.N. forces could
get in and get deployed," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah government had been trying to persuade the British
government to maintain its troops in his country but in vain.
</P>
<P>
According to Cook, despite the withdrawal, Britain still has a
three- point plan to help Sierra Leone: to repel the rebels,
restore the peace process and rebuild the country.
</P>
<P>
He promised "a very much hands-on involvement", saying that the
British government would "want to see this job through".
</P>
<P>
Cook also suggested an international embargo on rebel diamond
sales. The British government wants to consult with the United
States and the European Union on ways of achieving this, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he would also press for rebel leader Foday Sankoh,
currently under arrest, to be "brought to justice".
</P>
<P>
Serious clashes have been continuing in parts of the country
and gunfire was reported near pro-government militia leader Johnny
Paul Koroma's house in Freetown on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
According to a military spokesman, government forces retook
control of the strategic town of Lunsar on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lunsar, which is located on the road leading to the rebel
stronghold of Makeni and the eastern diamond fields, is the first
rebel position lost to the government since the counteroffensive
began after last month's hostage drama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
