<HEADLINE> Armed Conflict Costs Colombia 2 Pct GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Colombian economy will grow three percent this yer, but it
would go up to five percent were it not for the armed conflict
that has bled the country for 40 years and stunted its development,
said Cardenas at the Banking Convention being held in Bogota.
</P>
<P>
The official said that it is urgent to stop the armed
confrontation, or else it will go on costing a lot to the economy
and the society.
</P>
<P>
The country will have to assume during the next three years
costs close to seven billion U.S. dollars, an amount equal to
eight percent of the GDP, which would be used to bring back into
civilian life those now up in arms, assure them employment and
access to public services, according to recent studies made by the
DNP.  
</P>
