<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents of Golan Village Demonstrate Against Possible Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Residents of an Arab village on the
muffled border between Lebanon and the Israeli-occupied Golan
Heights of Syria have protested against a possible division of the
village in the United Nations' demarcation of the Lebanese-Israeli
border.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of residents of Ghajar village have staged tyre-burning
demonstrations since Wednesday and launched a general strike on
Thursday. They also threatened to bar the entry to the U.N. team in
charge of verifying Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon late
last month.
</P>
<P>
The residents learned last week from Israeli media that the U.N.
demarcation team indicated that the 1923 international border runs
through Ghajar village and that part of the village might be handed
over to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 1,700 residents of Ghajar are Alawite Muslims of
Syrian nationals. Many of them have taken Israeli citizenship after
the village, at the foot of the Golan Heights, was seized from
Syria by Israel in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Oriental radio reported that the head of Ghajar's
local council, Suliman Khatib, told the radio that the villagers "
would not be opposed to transferring the entire village to
Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
However, in a fax addressed to U.N. Mideast envoy Terje Roed
Larsen, the villagers said "official documents ... prove that our
land is Syrian and that we are Syrian and that we were occupied by
Israel in 1967." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Incident-Free Euro-2000 Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry on Friday
expressed hope to avoid incidents that might overshadow Turkey's
team's successes in the forthcoming Euro-2000 Football
Championship.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that measures, including
several warnings, had been taken in view of the Euro-2000 that will
take place in the Netherlands and Belgium between June 10 and July
2.
</P>
<P>
It added that a seven-member group had also been formed to help
and guide the Turkish team players and supporters during the Euro-
2000.
</P>
<P>
Violence broke out in Istanbul and Copenhagen between football
fans before the Union of European Football Association (UEFA) Cup
games in April and May. Two English fans were stabbed to death in
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the Foreign Ministry had thought it
beneficial to warn the Turkish citizens living in the Netherlands
and Belgium against possible provocations in order to prevent re-
occurrence of similar incidents during Euro-2000.
</P>
<P>
"We wish that all Turkish citizens should stay away from
attitudes and violence that may overshadow the Turkish team's
successes and harm the prestige of Turkey," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Turkish people and supporters, who watch the games, should
behave calmly without paying attention to provocations."
</P>
<P>
On May 17, Turkey's Galatasaray beat English's Arsenal 4-1 in a
penalty shoot-out after the UEFA Cup final finished 0-0 following
extra-time, winning its first European club trophy.
</P>
<P>
Victorious Turks have high hopes for Euro 2000, because 11
players from Galatasaray are in Turkey's pre-selection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
