<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges Rwanda. Uganda to Stop Fighting in Kisangani </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They appealed to Rwanda and Uganda for a cease of hostilities
immediately. The agencies are the World Food Program, the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees, the World Health Organization, the
U.N. Office for Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs and the U.N.
Children's Fund.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the governments of Rwanda and Uganda to immediately
end the fighting that is killing innocent civilians," they said in
a statement issued in U.N. headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
The entire civilian population of Kisangani was under fire and
completely cut off from humanitarian relief, with 19 children
killed recently, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
There was lack of water, food and electricity and dimmed
prospects for a major polio campaign, the U.N. Mission in
Kisangani has found.
</P>
<P>
Despite a ceasefire agreement by Rwanda and Uganda Thursday,
fighting continued for the fifth straight day with hundreds of
people reported to be dead or injured.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda used to be strong allies but now back
different rebel factions in the DRC. They have clashed for control
of Kisangani, a center of the DRC's diamond trade. 
