According to South African Press Association, Maope said
Lesotho's Independent Electoral Commission has told the government
that proper preparations for elections have not yet begun.
</P>
<P>
He said if preparations had started in May, the elections would
have been held in March or April next year but the present
problems would delay the process.
</P>
<P>
Maope said political parties are still grappling with two main
issues, namely disagreement on the electoral model to be used and
the restructuring of the senate.
</P>
<P>
There has been an agreement on the concept of a mixed member
electoral system but there is no consensus on how the seats will
be allocated under the proportional representation system, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Maope noted that the restructuring of senate is part of
Lesotho's Interim Political Authority's mandate to make it more
democratic and representative of the country and in terms of the
constitution, any change to the structure of the senate requires a
referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
