<HEADLINE> S. Africa Steps Up Efforts to Protect Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South African Water Affairs
Minister Ronnie Kasrils said on Friday that his ministry would
redouble efforts to prevent land pollution by the industry.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the parliament, Kasrils said he has set a
month-end deadline for resolution of the issue of polluted land
around Iscor's operations in the country. Iscor is the country's
iron and steel giant.
</P>
<P>
The matter had been dragging on for too long, he said in a
debate on his department's budget vote in the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
People who lived in the polluted area had suffered greatly,
their properties were worthless, and the earth had been poisoned,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week Kasrils met Iscor representatives and residents of
the surrounding area.
</P>
<P>
Kasrils announced earlier this week that he had appointed a
representative to conclude agreements on his behalf with Iscor and
the other parties involved. 
</P>
