<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela to Visit Burundi Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Former South African president
Nelson Mandela will fly to Burundi next Monday to meet leaders of
various armed groups and people living in the country's
controversial regroupment camps.
</P>
<P>
The former president will visit Burundi from June 12 to 14 as
chief mediator for the conflict in the Great Lakes country,
according to a statement issued by Mandela's office on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela met with Burundi President Pierre Buyoya in
Johannesburg on Wednesday and they reached an agreement to release
Burundians detained in the regroupment camps by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
The two statesmen also discussed the release of political
prisoners, some of whom have been held for seven years without
trial.
</P>
<P>
Although they did not reach any agreement on this aspect, they
undertook to discuss the matter again during Mandela's visit to
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
During forthcoming visit, Mandela is also expected to meet with
Burundi' s religious leaders, the judiciary, the cabinet, members
of the civil society groups and women's groups.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has invited Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni to
accompany him on the visit.
</P>
<P>
At least 200,000 people, both Hutus and Tutsis, have been
killed since October 1993 when the conflict between
Tutsi-dominated government and Hutu rebels broke out.
</P>
<P>
As mediator, Mandela is responsible for developing a formula
for a peaceful resolution to the conflict that can also be used as
a model for other African countries where ethnic tension has led
to political instability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
