<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Strengthen Scrutiny of Poverty Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) --The South African Department of
Finance plans to introduce new measures to monitor the
expenditure of poverty relief funds by government departments, a
senior official said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Government departments will in future have to submit quarterly
reports on poverty spending, said finance director-general Maria
Ramos while briefing the finance portfolio committee of the
parliament on supplementary estimates to the budget tabled earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
Government has distributed an extra 523.4 million rand (about
74.8 million U.S. dollars) to nine departments for poverty relief
and HIV/AIDS projects in the 2000/01 financial year, she said.
</P>
<P>
The funds form part of 1.2 billion rand (1.7 billion dollars)
budgeted for poverty relief and the sum of 75 million rand (10.07
million dollars) for HIV/Aids awareness campaigns.
</P>
<P>
With the budget deficit under control, the government's focus
should move toward making sure that funds allocated are spent
properly, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
"The real challenge for government going forward is to spend
the money that has been budgeted to spend," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to Ramos, six departments have asked if they could
roll over a total of 455.9 million rand (65.1 million dollars) in
poverty relief funds from the 1999/2000 financial year.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the unspent funds -- 256 million rand (36.5 million
dollars) -- came from the department of public works, while the
department of housing had 75 million rand (10.7 million dollars)
left and the department of welfare had 37.7 million rand (5.4
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The finance department would establish a "technical committee"
to advise government departments on poverty relief spending, Ramos
said.
</P>
<P>
It is also an exploring option to further involve the
Independent Development Trust in poverty project management, she
said, adding that it is well within the parliament's ambit to
summon government ministers and directors-general to answer
concerns about poverty spending.
</P>
<P>
The South African government allocated 653 million rand (93.2
million dollars) to poverty relief measures at the time of the
Budget, which together with the new disbursements, leaves 98.6
million rand (14 million dollars) unallocated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
