<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Continued Ceasefire Violations in Congo Disturbing: Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Continued ceasefire violations by
the rebel groups and foreign forces in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) are threatening the peace and stability of that
country, said Zimbabwean Defense Minister Moven Mahachi here on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a graduation ceremony for 56 junior staff officers
at the Zimbabwe Staff College, Mahachi said the repeated
violations, which were sometimes characterized by fierce fighting
among themselves, were disturbing enough to weaken the foundation
for peace in that part of the region.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda, former allies in the DRC conflict, went into
clashes again in the last few days, causing the death of about 50
people in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
At least 15 ceasefire agreements have been reached and
abandoned since the fighting between the two countries erupted on
Monday, Mahachi said.
</P>
<P>
According to the defense minister, a 20-man United Nations team
based in Kisangani failed to broker peace in the area because the
commanders of the rival Rwandan and Ugandan armies refused to
honor any peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The presence of the Joint Military Commission and the envisaged
arrival of a U.N. peacekeeping force in the DRC are expected to
arrest the situation from degenerating into further turmoil and
bloodshed, he said.
</P>
<P>
War is undesirable, he said, especially in the African
continent which is grappling to find solutions to the trouble in
Sierra Leone, the border dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea,
and the conflicts in Angola and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"The region awaits the speedy deployment of the U.N.
peacekeeping force with bated breadth," he said, adding that this
should kick off the systematic withdrawal of Zimbabwean troops as
provided for in the Lusaka peace agreement signed by all
belligerents in July and August last year.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola have been supporting DRC President
Laurent Kabila in fighting rebels in the country backed by Uganda
and Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
