<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Not to Beg Britain for Money: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Friday said his government will not ask for money from Britain to
fund the land resettlement program because the former colonial
power has failed to honor its promise on many occasions.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a campaign rally in Marange communal area of east
Zimbabwe, Mugabe said Britain had agreed to release funds on many
occasions when the Zimbabwean government embarked on the land
acquisition program after the expiry of the Lancaster House
constitution but never fulfilled the promise.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government would go ahead and take the land and
resettle thousands of peasants who had been deprived of their
ancestral land for many years, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are going ahead to take our land and resettle people with
the little resources we have," he said, adding that "but if
Britain wants to provide funds, it is welcome."
</P>
<P>
The president said his government has never refused to pay
compensation to white farmers as long as Britain provides the
funds. Zimbabweans could not pay for their land, he said.
</P>
<P>
He lashed out at British Prime Minister Tony Blair, accusing
him of refusing to support the land program and creating many
problems the country is facing.
</P>
<P>
According to Mugabe, in 1996 the Conservative British
government of John Major agreed to fund the resettlement program
and invited him to London for talks.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was reached on the release of funds but
unfortunately this failed to materialize because Major lost the
election to Blair, he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about white commercial farmers, the president said they
are like Blair who never wants to see blacks being given their
land. Instead, he said, the whites supported and funded the
opposition Movement for Democratic Change (MDC) in a bid to take
back their properties.
</P>
<P>
According to Mugabe, the actions of the white farmers to oppose
the Draft Constitution and force their workers to support the MDC
angered war veterans and youths of the ruling Zimbabwe African
National Union-Patriotic Front.
</P>
<P>
"I did not order them to invade the farms as their patron, but
they did it on their own," he said, warning that people would soon
target other whites in the mines and factories.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would soon introduce price controls as
producers are profiteering at the expense of suffering people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
