<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen's tourist revenues will hike from 70 million U.S.
dollars in 1999 to 100 million dollars by the end of 2000,
according to Chairman of the General Tourist Authority (GTA) Abdul-
Rahman Maihub, who added that the GTA plans to raise the tourist
revenues in 2001 to 150-200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
A total of 20 new hotels were opened over the last week in
several provinces to accommodate more tourists.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian firms were awarded contracts in Lebanon
amounting in value to 170 million dollars. Among the contracted
projects are the constructions of the New Lebanese University, the
40-kilometer Tripoli-Zogorta highway and a sanitary drainage
station in Sidon.
</P>
<P>
Egypt exported 28,750 tons of potatoes to Lebanon at a value of
6.3 million dollars in 1999 and is trying to export other
commodities such as rice and electrical products to the country.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- "Middle East 2000 -- First Middle East Industry Fair"
will be organized in southeastern Diyarbakir Province between
September 27 and October 3.
</P>
<P>
Sevket Akalin, general coordinator of the International Fair and
Foreign Trade Company, said on Friday the preparations for the fair
are underway.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Industry Federation, among others, will join the fair,
said Akalin, adding that "We hope this fair will be the beginning
of the relations we desire to have with our neighboring countries.
We target at improving the regional trade and directing our
products to the foreign markets, starting from the neighboring
countries."
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Anex An Express, a private Turkish airlines company,
has got licence from the Transportation Ministry and will start its
flights at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
The company's president, Sadi Erguvenc, said on Friday that the
company would fly mainly to European countries in addition to
domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
The company will start flights with three American MD-80 planes,
which will be reinforced with a couple of Brazilian ERJ-145 jets in
November.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Bulgaria has sent a new draft agreement on preventing
double taxation to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Bulgaria decided to revoke a 15-year treaty with
Cyprus on avoiding double taxation.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's decision was aimed to curtail money laundering and
black economy of the country and to stop people living in Bulgaria
from setting up businesses in Cyprus and using them to siphon
incomes and profits out of Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Finance Minister Takis Clerides said the deal is expected
to be clinched by the end of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
