<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Steps Up Excavation at Ancient Zeugma Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is accelerating excavations at
the ancient city Zeugma, a Roman ruin in southern Gaziantep
Province, which will soon be submerged by the Birecik Dam.
</P>
<P>
Mehmet Onal, the archaeologist responsible for the excavations,
on Friday praised President Ahmet Sezer's decision to extend the
date when the dam across the Euphrates River would release water,
as part of the government's ambitious plans to generate electricity
and irrigate vast areas of dry land.
</P>
<P>
However, the extension by 10 days is not enough, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We have found two of the Roman villas at the site. Despite all
our efforts, a part of the history will remain in darkness by the
inundation because we do not have sufficient time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zeugma, hailed as a "second Pompeii" by archaeologists who have
unearthed valuable relics there, can be marked into three
archaeological zones, two of which are scheduled to be inundated in
June and October respectively.
</P>
<P>
But the third and greatest part of the site will not be drowned
by the reservoir, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Zeugma was a summer place of the wealthy Roman people living on
the banks of Euphrates River, who brought some of the best artists
of the time there, Onal said, adding that the unique mosaics and
frescos unearthed at the site had been transferred to the Gaziantep
Archeology Museum.
</P>
<P>
"Zeugma, which is only five meters under the soil, is the way to
reach the people who lived 2,000 years ago, to recognize them and
to see their artifacts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, Southeastern Anatolia Project Regional
Development Administration, a Turkish governmental agency on
sustainable development, signed a memo of understanding with
Packard Humanities Institute (PHI), a California-based foundation
in the United States, to reinforce the emergency rescue work at
Zeugma.
</P>
<P>
The PHI has agreed to earmark a budget of 5 million U.S. dollars
for the excavation, conservation and study of Zeugma.
</P>
<P>
Turkey boasts of numerous ancient Greek and Roman cities with
antiquities that are among the finest and most abundant in the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
