<HEADLINE> Aftershocks Rock Northern Turkey, No Injuries Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 9 (xinhua) -- Two moderate aftershocks hit Cerkes
township of Cankiri Province, some 100 kilometers north of the
Turkish capital Ankara, early Friday morning, said the Anatolia
News Agency. No casualties or damage were reported so far.
</P>
<P>
The first tremor, measuring 5.0 on the Richter scale, jolted
Cerkes at 0:28 a.m. (2128 GMT), the Bogazici University Kandilli
Observatory Center and Seismology Institute said.
</P>
<P>
The second aftershock, with a magnitude of 5.2, struck at 6:14
a.m. (0314 GMT), the report said. It was also felt in the
surrounding provinces.
</P>
<P>
Both tremors were aftershocks of the 5.9-magnitude earthquake
which rocked Cerkes at 5:41 a.m. (0241 GMT) on Tuesday, killing
three people, injuring dozens and damaging thousands of houses.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, an earthquake-prone country with some areas situated
along fault belts, suffered two devastating earthquakes last year,
a 7.4-magnitude one in the Marmara region in August and a 7.2-
magnitude one in November in the Bolu Province.
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 people were killed in the two quakes and the
property losses were estimated at 20 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
