<HEADLINE> Analysis: Consumption Turns Out to Be Engine of China's Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Consumption has turned out to be
the major growth engine in China while the government's
infrastructure program is still the driving force for investment
growth.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the widely-held argument that China's economy is
driven by the government investment and exports, analysts from the
Hong Kong-based bank Standard and Chartered believed that the
strong recovery is actually rather broadly based.
</P>
<P>
The country has registered a robust growth in the first quarter
in retail sales, investment, exports and imports, but as far as
the contribution to growth is concerned, the recovery is led by
consumption, they said.
</P>
<P>
A report carried in the latest issue of Viewpoints released by
the bank on Friday also showed that the contribution of
consumption to China's gross domestic product (GDP) growth
increased to 62 percent in the first quarter this year from 49
percent in 1998, while the contribution from investment declined
to 26 percent from 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the government's infrastructure program is
still the driving force for investment growth, but its role in
driving GDP growth has been greatly reduced. Consumption has begun
to replace investment as the major growth engine, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Further studies made by the bank indicated that it is true that
export growth has become more pronounced as a result of a robust
recovery in the East Asian economies, but for a big "continental'
economy such as China, the level of consumption is ultimately the
main determinant of economic growth in the long term.
</P>
<P>
Economists here also said that now that China's consumption
growth has stabilized and become the key economic driver, the
coming phase of economic expansion will be more sustainable.
</P>
<P>
"There is no lack of driving forces for consumption growth in
China at this development stage," the economists said. They
expected an annual rise of at least 10 percent in China's consumer
services consumption in the coming decade since the tertiary
sector accounts for less than 30 percent of its GDP.
</P>
<P>
Taken together with the consumption growth in other aspects,
they said, there are reasons to expect potential consumption
growth at the present stage of development to exceed seven percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
China's consumption growth has experienced both a structural
and a cyclical slowdown since 1994 because of as a rapid
improvement in the living standard of the people in the past two
decades and the reform of state-owned enterprises and the
consequential reform of the pension, employment, housing,
education and medical care systems in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the consumption slowdown to a three-year
austerity program by the government, which checked the overheating
of both consumption and investment during the period from 1992 to
1994.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the current consumption-boosting policy, they
said it helps revive the cyclical slowdown, but focuses too much
on investment and urban consumption. "The effects of the
government's infrastructure program remains less-than-expected,
and rural consumption is still out of reach of the policy," they
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
However, they believed that helped by China's imminent
accession to the World Trade Organization, China's consumption
growth prospects will continue to improve with a GDP growth of
about eight percent in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
