<HEADLINE> Manila Rules out Deadline for Talks on Hostages' Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Contrary to reports, Philippine
President Joseph Estrada did not set a June 12 deadline for the
safe release of 21 hostages held by the Abu Sayyaf in Jolo, the
presidential palace said.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing, Press Undersecretary Mike Toledo said the
president merely wanted to have "substantial" developments in the
negotiations to take place by then.
</P>
<P>
"The president didn't impose any deadline on the negotiating
panel. Negotiations such as this situation cannot be time bound.
The president did say he would want some substantial developments
by June 12," Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, reports claimed that the president gave the
negotiating panel up to June 12 to secure the release of the 21
hostages.
</P>
<P>
But Toledo said the president merely "expressed the desire to
have some substantive results in the next couple of days."
</P>
<P>
When asked what would happen if the hostages are not released
by June 12, Toledo said the negotiations would still continue.
</P>
<P>
He said the most substantive result would be the hostages' safe
release, adding that the panel members are "optimistic" that "
there would be something substantive" that could happen by June 12.
</P>
<P>
Toledo also said the government panel headed by Robert
Aventajado has received word from the hostage takers that they
want their leader Khadafy Janjalani included in the talks.
</P>
<P>
The president, he further said, has given the government panel
"full authority and discretion" to make decisions on the ground,
though substantive decisions would have to be brought to the
president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
