<HEADLINE> S.Lankan Govt, Opposition Talk Peace Amid Fierce Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government of People
's Alliance Friday continued peace talks with the main opposition
United National Party (UNP) as fierce fighting raged between
government troops and Tamil Tiger rebels in the northern Jaffna
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Two delegations, led respectively by President Kumaratunga and
UNP leader Wickremesinghe, had discussed the key land issue in the
radical power-sharing constitutional reforms, aimed at ending the
17-year ethnic conflicts between majority Sinhalese and minority
Tamils.
</P>
<P>
"The two delegations continued the discussions on provisions
relating to land in the proposed constitution, agreement was
reached on several matters," said a joint communique issued by the
two parties.
</P>
<P>
It said the subcommittee on land will consider the remaining
issues and report to the plenary.
</P>
<P>
During the talks President Kumaratunga emphasized the need to
reach agreement on all matters relating to the proposed
constitution expeditiously, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga had said she was keen to conclude talks with the
UNP by mid-June and press ahead with the constitutional reforms at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believed that a bipartisan approach between the
government and the UNP was crucial for any peace process to
succeed, as together they represent almost the entire majority
Sinhalese community.
</P>
<P>
Any agreement between the two main parties must be presented to
parliament and approved before it stands automatically dissolved
on August 24. Thereafter, fresh elections must be held by mid-
November.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fierce fighting erupted in Jaffna on Friday with
Tamil Tiger rebels launching a dawn attack on military defenses
around the town of Koddikamam but troops had beaten back the rebel
assault.
</P>
<P>
The rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have been
fighting for a separate state for Tamils in the country's north
and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, who were accused of assassinating Minister of
Industrial Development C. V. Gunaratne on Wednesday, have opposed
the government's constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, Norway has been trying to bring the LTTE and the Sri
Lankan government to the negotiating table even as both sides
remained locked in fierce combat in Jaffna. 
</P>
</TEXT>
