<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zimbabwe to Speed Up Land Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government is facing
mounting pressure to accelerate land redistribution to thousands
of landless peasants in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The land issue which has been an emotive one since the turn of
the century took the front seat in February this year when war
veterans of the 1970s liberation struggle occupied more than 1,500
white-owned commercial farms.
</P>
<P>
Farm occupations by war veterans were met with resistance.
Five white farmers were allegedly murdered by war veterans and
their supporters in clashes that resulted in the damage of crops
and equipment worth millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans who have the support of President Robert
Mugabe vow that they will not leave the farms until the 804 farms
gazetted by the government in June are distributed to the
landless.
</P>
<P>
"As war veterans we are saying we want the government to move
fast and allocate land to people before the parliamentary
elections are held on June 24 and 25," said Zimbabwe National
Liberation War Veterans Association leader Chenjerai Hunzvi.
</P>
<P>
Facing this pressure, the government issued a preliminary
notice to compulsorily acquire 804 farms for resettlement
following the passage of the Constitutional Amendment Act and the
amendment of the Land Acquisition Act of 1992.
</P>
<P>
The amendments are intended to assure speedier land acquisition
by allowing the government to seize white-owned farms without
paying compensation.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980, the land delivery processes have been cumbersome
and very slow as the "willing seller, willing buyer" promulgated
in the 1979 Lancaster House Agreement before Zimbabwe's
independence did not bring the intended results of giving land to
the majority of the people.
</P>
<P>
The Lancaster House Constitution prevented speedier land
delivery by outlawing constitutional reforms on land ownership for
the first 10 years to 1990.
</P>
<P>
After 1991, Zimbabwean government efforts to resettle people
were undermined by lack of funding for the land reform program.
</P>
<P>
The British government, which undertook to be the main donor of
Zimbabwe' s land reform program during the independence
negotiations in 1979, had promised to bankroll the exercise to the
tune of 30 million British pounds.
</P>
<P>
But Britain withdrew its support claiming that Mugabe was
giving the land to his "cronies and political allies".
</P>
<P>
Later it also said it would release the money for land reform
only on condition that violence and farm invasions end.
</P>
<P>
Since then Mugabe and British Prime Minister Tony Blair have
traded a war of words over the land issue.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has rejected such conditions saying Britain has a
historic obligation to provide the money.
</P>
<P>
Threats by other western countries to isolate Zimbabwe, impose
economic sanctions and cut donor aid have also added to the woes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zimbabwe to Speed Up Land Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For lack of funds, the Zimbabwean government acquired only 3.5
million hectares between 1980 and 1990 and resettled 71,000
families out of a target of 162,000.
</P>
<P>
More are expected to be resettled on other 55 farms already
owned by the state.
</P>
<P>
And the glaring disparity in land ownership in this southern
African nation of more than 12.5 million people has forced blacks
to speak up despite the economic dangers that go with it.
</P>
<P>
At least 4,500 white commercial farmers own 75 percent of
arable land, or about 11.2 million hectares, with the majority of
people crowded in unproductive land.
</P>
<P>
About one million black communal farmers are still farming on
marginal soils, 16.3 million hectares in all.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, land plays the important role in social stability
and economic development in rural areas, where 70 percent of the
country's population live.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe recently said the revolutionary struggle to liberate the
country was not finished until land was given to the people.
</P>
<P>
He said in addition to the 804 farms that were gazetted for
acquisition, the government would look for more to add to the
list to speed up the land reform. "The next Parliament must take
bold measures to solve the land issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The wave of farm invasions also threatens to spill to
neighboring countries like South Africa and Namibia which have
similar problems to that of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
South African President Thabo Mbeki secured 15 million U.S.
dollars in May from Norwegian and Saudi governments in a bid to
end farm invasions and defuse tension before the Zimbabwean
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said this will also add pressure on the Zimbabwean
government to speedily distribute land to its people.
</P>
<P>
Critics charged that the land issue is the last trump card for
Mugabe who is facing dwindling support because of high
unemployment, fuel and electricity shortages as well as
skyrocketing prices of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
They said that Mugabe is using the land issue to divert
attention from the crumbling economy with more than 50 percent
unemployment, 60 percent interest rates and critical shortage of
foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said it is only after elections that violence and farm
 invasions will end. But war veterans leader Hunzvi said, "Every
person in Zimbabwe has a right to land. We want our land. We
will not stop until our people get back their land." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
