<HEADLINE> Uganda Accuses Rwanda of Violating Newly-Reached Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Friday accused the Rwandan
Patriotic Army (RPA) of attacking all the positions of the Uganda
People's Defence Forces which lasted three and half hours in
violation of a newly-reached ceasefire by multi-parties.
</P>
<P>
"The RPA launched a massive and persistent attack on all UPDF
positions lasting three and half hours," James Wapakabulo,
chairman of National Coordination Committee on the Region, told a
press conference Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The UPDF, remaining in its defence, repulsed all the attacks,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Following Uganda's proposal for a unilateral ceasefire in
Kisangani, a Tele-Conference was held on Thursday and participated
in by Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni, Rwandan President Paul
Kagame, U.N. Secretary- General Kofi Annan, Ambassador of the
United States to the U.N. R. Holbrooke and U.S. Assistant
Secretary of State for Africa Susan Rice.
</P>
<P>
The conference agreed that the UPDF and RPA cease fire at 16:00
 Kisangani time, according to Wapakabulo.
</P>
<P>
"In total disregard to the ceasefire agreement resulting from
the Tele- Conference, the RPA launched attacks again on our
positions Friday morning, which have also been repulsed," said
Wapakabulo.
</P>
<P>
"The RPA has persistently taken hostile measures to frustrate
U.N. deployment of the observers," he said, referring to the
unilateral ceasefire declared by Uganda Thursday given
preconditions of U.N. establishing an observer presence on the
UPDF side.
</P>
<P>
Uganda accused the Rwandan government of "flagrant breach" of
an agreement reached by the parties in the Tele-Conference and
Uganda's unilateral offer of ceasefire on Thursday, said
Wapakabulo.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops started to shell each other in
Kisangani, a northeastern city of the Democratic Republic of the
Congo, after a UPDF's vehicle was attacked and destroyed Monday
morning. The fighting was the latest following clashes between the
two armies in early May.
</P>
<P>
The two former allies have their troops stationed in Kisangani
where they have backed rival rebel factions fighting against the
DRC President Laurent Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
