<HEADLINE> No World Cup Bid Deal with S.Africa, Says Morocco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RABAT, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Morocco said on Friday it would not
withdraw from the bid race to host the 2006 World Cup finals,
which broke Johannesburg's hopes of a possible deal during a visit
at the weekend by South African Sports Minister Ngconde Balfour.
</P>
<P>
South African officials said on Thursday that Balfour would try
to persuade Morocco to quit the race, leaving South Africa as the
only African candidate.
</P>
<P>
"Our brotherly South Africans are very welcome to visit us any
time they want. But they should not be under any illusion that
this means the slightest concession in our campaign to host the
2006 World Cup," Driss Benhima, vice-president of Morocco's bid
committee, was quoted by Reuters as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We have accepted to meet the South African delegation but we
really don't know what the agenda would be," Benhima said.
</P>
<P>
FIFA's 24-man executive committee will meet in Zurich on July 5
and 6 to choose the winner of the bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
