<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Calls for Closer Economic Cooperation With Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian Foreign Minister Nadezhda
Mikhailova expressed hope on Friday that the trade and economic
cooperation between Bulgaria and Egypt will match their "
distinguished political ties."
</P>
<P>
At the close of her three-day visit in Cairo, Mikhailova said in
an interview with Egypt's Middle East News Agency that there are
diverse potentials for economic cooperation, particularly in the
engineering, chemical, military and machinery industries, between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria and Egypt have much in common in the economic
conditions, a similarity which can be a good basis for cooperation,
she said. She expressed regret that bilateral trade is current at a
low level of about 50 million U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria held an exhibition of agricultural products in Egypt
last year, which will be reciprocated by an Egyptian product
display in Bulgaria's capital Sofia in October, she added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Mideast peace process, the Bulgarian minister
said her country supports the establishment of an independent
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she called on the Palestinians to declare an
independent state after reaching a final peace agreement with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel are negotiating for a final
settlement of thorny issues including the fate of Jerusalem, Jewish
settlements, borders, Palestinian refugees and water.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian official also hoped that Syria and Israel would
resume peace negotiations, which broke down in January due to
disputes over Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights it seized
from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
"Peace in the Middle East would not be permanent and
comprehensive without the participation of Syria, which is an
important factor in the region," Mikhailova added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
