<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Computer Professionals Hail Industry-Boosting Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Computer Society (BCS) and
Bangladesh Association for Software and Information Services (
BASIS) hailed the proposed budget for 2000-2001 fiscal for
withdrawing value-added taxes (VAT) from all computer systems, a
press release said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the press release, the presidents of BCS and BASIS said
withdrawal of VAT from all computer systems, parts and software at
production and supply stages and extension of tax holiday would
encourage greater use of computers for higher efficiency and
productivity.
</P>
<P>
Appreciating government's allocation of 150 million taka (2.9
million U.S. dollars) for development of programmers, they also
said the measures and "Equity Development Fund" for development of
software industry would give a boost to growing software export
industry.
</P>
<P>
In the budget for fiscal year 2000-2001 unveiled by Finance
Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria Thursday, proposals have been made for
total exemption of last fiscal's 15 percent supplementary duties
on modem, CD-ROM, drive, CD and software for accelerating the pace
of software industry.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has withdrawn customs duty and tax from computer
imports since 1998. However, Kibria lamented that the withdrawal
was yet to yield any major impact on the growth of the country's
software industry.
</P>
<P>
But the finance minister said the government will continue to
take concrete measures for ensuring transition to knowledge-based
industry, as "the benefits of knowledge-based growth will not
automatically accrue to developing countries like Bangladesh."
</P>
</TEXT>
