<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Sowing GM-Rapeseed Get Reimbursed: EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- European farmers who sowed
imported genetically-modified rapeseed seeds unknowingly will be
reimbursed, the European Union said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers should not suffer financially from a situation they
were not responsible for," said EU Farm Commissioner Franz
Fischler.
</P>
<P>
The seeds imported from Canada contained a small amount of
genetically-modified material.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
bloc, was still to consider how much money to pay for the farmers
in Britain, France and Germany where imported genetically-modified
rapeseed seeds were sown.
</P>
<P>
A commission spokesperson said Friday that the crops could not
be sold anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
The commission's decision to reimburse the farmers was approved
by the EU member states Friday at their cereals management
committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
The EU rules that the plants should have been left in the field
until flowering or June 30 for the usual area payment under the
union's Common Agricultural Policy.
</P>
<P>
The company that imported the genetically-modified rapeseed
seeds has agreed to compensate for the losses sustained by the
farmers in the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Some farmers, however, have already removed the crops when it
became known that they had sown genetically-modified rapeseed
seeds and the crops could no longer be marketed.
</P>
<P>
Farmers can now sow a new spring crop or leave the field fallow
until this autumn, the European Commission said.
</P>
<P>
Another payment will be made for the new sowing of the crop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
