<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Players Each Game to Have Doping Tests in Euro 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- European soccer's governing body
UEFA will dope-test two players randomly selected from each team
at all matches during the Euro 2000 tournament.
</P>
<P>
The players' numbers will be decided by draw during the
halftime break and the respective teams will be informed 15
minutes before the match end.
</P>
<P>
The players selected have to report to the doping center some
30 minutes after the end of the match. The period of time is for
them to shower and change and to talk to the media before going to
provide their urine sample.
</P>
<P>
Eight UEFA officers will supervise the test procedure, assisted
by a representative of the government authorities in one of the co-
hosts, Belgium or the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Samples will be analysed at International Olympic Committee
accredited laboratories in Belgium or the German city of Cologne.
But the two laboratories will stay distant from urine samples of
players from their countries.
</P>
<P>
There have been no high profile doping cases during the finals
of European championships, but Diego Maradona was thrown out of
the 1994 World Cup finals in the United States after he tested
positive for banned substances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
