<HEADLINE> Australian PM's Plane Makes Emergency Landing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF)
VIP plane carrying Prime Minister John Howard and opposition
leader Kim Beazley was forced to make an emergency landing in
Brisbane Friday night after a warning light showed an engine was
on fire.
</P>
<P>
The aging aircraft was returning to Australia from Japan where
the Australian prime minister had attended the funeral of the late
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
But about two hours out of Brisbane, capital of Australia's
Queensland state, an emergency light indicated a fire in one of
the plane four engines.
</P>
<P>
The captain asked Brisbane airport to have emergency crews on
standby for the landing.
</P>
<P>
"There were indications of a fire in the number one engine," an
RAAF spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Purely as a precautionary measure, the engine was shut down
and the fire extinguisher discharged," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the captain believed the warning was "
spurious" but they treated it seriously for safety measures.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the same plane was delayed about an hour in Tokyo
because strong winds made it dangerous to take off.
</P>
<P>
The government is considering leasing a new fleet of VIP
aircraft to replace the aging old one but the cabinet is yet to
make a firm decision.
</P>
<P>
Despite Friday night's incident, the plane landed safely and
the prime minister proceeded to Sydney on another aircraft.
</P>
</TEXT>
