<HEADLINE> Former Indonesian President's House Arrest Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Attorney General's
Office(AGO) has extended former President Soeharto's house arrest
for another one month as of June 12.
</P>
<P>
The letter of extension was sent by Director of Corruption
Affairs of the AGO Ris Pandapotan Sihombing to Soeharto's
residence here Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
AGO Spokesman Yushar Yahya told reporters that the decision was
taken to accelerate the ongoing investigation into alleged
corruption by the former president.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, 78, had been under city arrest and banned from
leaving the country since early April and he has undergone
questioning several times at his residence for corruption charges.
He was put under house arrest on May 29.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto is suspected of abusing power and authority by issuing
decrees and government regulations to amass funds through seven
tax-free charity foundations he set up and chaired during his 32
years in power.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Marzuki Darusman has pledged that Soeharto
will be brought to justice before August 10. 
</P>
