<HEADLINE> Warring Groups in Solomon Islands Agree on Short Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Warring groups in the Solomon
Islands Friday night agreed on a two-day cease-fire to allow a
weekend visit by the Australian foreign minister and his
Commonwealth delegation, the Australian Associated Press (AAP)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The AAP said the two groups in the Solomons fighting over
ethnic land rights on the country's main island of Guadalcanal
Friday failed to negotiate a 14-day truce.
</P>
<P>
But they agreed on the shorter cease-fire to allow Australian
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer and his delegation to visit.
</P>
<P>
Downer and his New Zealand counterpart, Phil Goff, are prepared
to fly into Honiara, capital of the Solomon Islands, Friday night
as the situation in the capital remained calm.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand High Commissioner in Honiara Nick Hurley was quoted
by the AAP as saying the Commonwealth delegation is expected to
land by military plane at Honiara's Henderson Field international
airport Saturday morning (local time).
</P>
<P>
The delegation is aiming to bring a conciliatory end to the
country's week-long attempted coup after the Malaita Eagle Force (
MEF) captured Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu at gunpoint on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The MEF have signed a truce to the effect that there won't be
any (military) activity during the visit," Hurley said.
</P>
<P>
"On paper, at least, the truce is good while the ministers are
here," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the opposing rebel group, the Isatabu Freedom Movement
(IFM), had declared their own cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Downer's delegation is expected to stay in Honiara for only one
day.
</P>
<P>
There was no fresh fighting reported on Friday between the MEF
and the IFM after up to 100 people were reportedly killed in
raging gun battles earlier this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
