<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economic Growth to Reach 5 to 6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economy is expected to
grow by 5 to 6 percent in the medium term or in 2004 and 2005, a
senior economic minister said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The (Indonesian) government targets the economic growth at 3
to 4 percent in the year 2000, and at 5 to 6 percent in the medium
term or in 2004 and 2005," Coordinating Minister for Economy,
Finance, and Industry Kwik Kian Gie said.
</P>
<P>
"The government also has hammered out a plan to keep the
inflation rate at the level of 5 percent (this year)," Kwik said.
</P>
<P>
He is optimistic that the government will be able to meet the
targets.
</P>
<P>
"Data from the Central Bureau of Statistic (BPS) showed that
exports during January-March this year increased by 38.7 percent
against the same period last year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kwik also said the current economic growth is on a solid basis.
</P>
<P>
But he cautioned that the country's foreign debt has become a
heavy burden for the government budget.
</P>
<P>
"If we want to learn from the past, our foreign borrowing
should be reduced step by step," Kwik added.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent report of the World Bank, the economic
crisis has increased the Indonesian government's debt to 134
billion U.S. dollars or about 83 percent of the country's gross
domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
It also said the government would need new external and
domestic financing in the coming years to meet expenditure needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
