<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Buses Launched in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Tourist buses have been launched
here recently to attract tourists to spend more time in the city
and help them get around on their own, the Tourism Authority of
Thailand (TAT) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The lush green double-decker buses, run by the Bangkok
Metropolitan Administration, can now be seen making the rounds of
some of the Thai capital's most frequently visited tourist
landmarks, the TAT said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The bus program is particularly designed to appeal to a growing
number of independent tourists who like exploring on their own and
is also in line with the city's campaign to boost its chances of
winning the bid for the 2008 Olympic Games, the TAT said.
</P>
<P>
The service operates every day, charging a round-trip fee of
200 baht (5.2 U.S. dollars). A guide provides an English language
introduction of the historic highlights of 30 tourist landmarks in
Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The specially designed 50-seat buses are equipped with an
environment-friendly engine to minimize air pollution. The lower
deck provides elegant and comfortable seats with a teakwood
interior and a toilet while the upper one offers an open-air view.
</P>
<P>
TAT Governor Pradech Phayakvichien was quoted as saying tourist
buses are one of the basic tourist facilities in any city, adding
that the TAT will help distribute information about the service
to all its international offices as well as through its brochures
and website. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
