<HEADLINE> Rising Trend Reversed on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Share prices nose-dived on the
Singapore Stock Market Friday on profit-taking triggered by an
overnight slump in U.S. stocks, reversing the rising movement in
six straight sessions of gains this month.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) shed 17.66 points to
end the day at 2,042.61 in light trading.
</P>
<P>
The total volume amounted to 329 million shares worth 604.57
million Singapore dollars (350.58 million U.S. dollars). There
were 128 advancers against 167 decliners with 225 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was a 17.22 million parcel by L&AMP;M which was
transacted at 0.815 Singapore dollars per share. It was followed
by the Kingboard which had 16.51 million units done. AsiaDekor was
the next with 16.5 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
PacCent topped the gainers list as it soared 260 cents to close
at 16.9 Singapore dollars. Creative 50 surged up 190 cents
finishing the day at 48.4 Singapore dollars. Global Tech gained 34
cents to end at 2 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Venture was the top loser as it gave up 60 cents to close at 18.
6 Singapore dollars. DBS also tumbled by 60 cents to finish at 21.
2 Singapore dollars while OCBC retreated 50 cents to end at 10.9
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed Friday's fall to profit-taking because
investors cashed in profits on recent hefty pickup in the six
straight days of gains.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the fall led by banking and technology stocks
occurred on profit-taking that was triggered by an overnight fall
in U.S. stocks. 
</P>
