<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Rebels Target Wrong Minister in Suicide Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil Tiger rebels may
have had another senior minister instead of Minister of Industrial
Development C. V. Gunaratne as their target in a suicide bombing
Wednesday, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The rebel target would have been Minister of Justice and
Constitutional Affairs G. L. Peiris," said Raja Alwis, a member of
the Dehiwala-Mount Lavinia Municipal Council in the southern
suburb of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Gunaratne was killed Wednesday in the bombing when he was
leading a procession to collect donations for the army at
Ratmalana in Dehiwala-Mount Lavinia, the minister's constituency.
</P>
<P>
Minister Peiris, who is considered as a prime target for the
rebels, represents a constituency adjoining Gunaratne's.
</P>
<P>
Peiris was due to join the procession but he failed to show up,
Alwis said, adding that Gunaratne who was to turn back instead
walked up to the point where the suicide bomber carried out the
attack.
</P>
<P>
The bombing was blamed on the separatist rebels of the
Liberation Tiger of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), who have plotted a string
of similar attacks in the capital since December as a part of
their 17-year campaign to carve out a homeland for minority Tamils
in Sri Lanka's north and east.
</P>
<P>
The toll in the bombing had risen to 25 by Thursday evening
with Gunaratne's wife, Shyama, and two others, who were among 60
people injured in the blast, succumbing to their injuries,police
said.
</P>
<P>
Minister Gunaratne's body was brought to the local municipal
council on Friday for people to pay their last respects.
</P>
<P>
People from all walks of life paid their last respects to the
slain minister, who will be accorded a state funeral Saturday
evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
