<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Tanzanian Regions Face Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Some nine out of the total 25
regions in Tanzania are facing acute food shortage following
shortage of rains during the 1999/2000 farming season.
</P>
<P>
The official Daily News Friday quoted the Director of the
Strategic Grain Reserve (SGR) Department in the Tanzanian Ministry
of Agriculture and Cooperatives Albert Lazaro Ngondo as saying
that about 5.7 billion Tanzanian shillings (about 7.13 million
U.S. dollars) will be needed to replenish the food stock.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye on the food
situation after he visited several SGR silos in Dar es Salaam on
Thursday, the director mentioned the affected as the eastern
regions of Arusha, Kilimanjaro, Tanga, Morogoro, central regions
of Dodoma, Singida and western regions of Shinyanga, Mwanza and
Tabora.
</P>
<P>
He told the premier his department is sending food to the
affected areas and by the end of this month, the SGR food stock
will decline from the present 82,199 tons to 70,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, about 65,000 tons of maize will
have to be secured from areas which received sufficient amount of
rains to enable SGR boost its stock to 135,000 tons by next
September.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye directed the department to use funds collected from sale
of food to the affected regions to replenish the stock.
</P>
<P>
The premier also challenged Tanzanians to cultivate the culture
of preserving food after harvest and make proper use of the little
that is available.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years, Tanzania received an assistance of just
60,000 tons of food from donors despite its appeal for 900,000
tons of grain.
</P>
<P>
Of the 88.6 million hectares of arable land in the country,
only about half is currently being exploited, leaving millions of
Tanzanians in a constant state of hunger.
</P>
<P>
Rain-fed and hand-hoe agriculture has never improve over the
last half century and the country remains vulnerable to hunger and
starvation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
