<HEADLINE> Nigerian Strike Organizers Reject Government Concession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian government have agreed to
reduce the petrol price to 25 naira (0. 25 U. S dollar) from it
formerly designated 30 naira (0. 30 dollar), but the offer was
rejected by the Nigeria National Labor Congress (NLC), organizer
of the ongoing national strike.
</P>
<P>
This was a major concession the government made to the "labor
and people of Nigeria", said Doyin Okupe, special Assistant to
the President on Media and Publicity Thursday in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
He, however, added that the resulted five naira (0.05 dollar)
rise in petrol price will not be enough to maintain adequate
supplies but it would be used to sustain part of the importation
costs pending the return of full production of Nigeria' s
domestic refineries.
</P>
<P>
He said the government still believed that it was imperative to
fully deregulate the sector within the next 12 months, adding
that a committee would be raised to involve organized labors,
employers, and other relevant consumer groups in formulating
cushioning effects of future fuel price hikes.
</P>
<P>
Most of the big cities across Nigeria came to a standstill when
the nation wide "sit at home" strike began on Thursday morning.
In some state capitals, the strike was dotted with violence,
reportedly leading to the death and arrest of people.
</P>
<P>
A motorist was killed in Lagos, Nigeria' s economic hub and
protesters torched the state House of Kano in the north of the
country.
</P>
<P>
In order to stop the strike, representatives of Nigerian
President Olusegun Obasanjo Thursday invited NLC President Adams
Oshiomhole to an emergency meeting in the capital. But Oshiomhole
said after the meeting that his organization would not go back on
the strike if the Federal Government refused to rescind the hike
and recover the old petrol price.
</P>
<P>
NLC called for the general strike shortly after the Nigerian
government increased the country's petrol price by 50 percent to
30 naira (100 naira equals about one U.S. dollar) per liter on
last Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
