<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Calls for Better Protection of World's Marine Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF)
has called on governments and local communities around the world
to find new ways of protecting the world's vital marine resources.
</P>
<P>
The recent estimates suggest that up to 80 percent of the
world's protected marine areas are not being managed effectively,
the world conservation organization said in its press release
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Though properly managed protected marine areas can provide a
range of benefits for fishers, conservation and local economies,
increased resources are urgently needed to make this happen.
</P>
<P>
"Today less than one percent of the world's seas is within
marine protected areas," said Scott Burns, director of the WWF's
Endangered Seas Campaign. "A large proportion of these are
protected in name only because they are poorly managed."
</P>
<P>
There is growing evidence that within two to five years, fully
protected marine reserves - also called "no-fishing zones" - can
turn the tide on overfishing and provide real ecological and
economic benefits to local communities.
</P>
<P>
In fully protected marine reserves, the fish live longer and
grow larger. Increased production of offspring within reserves
also helps to restock nearby fishing grounds, allowing fishers to
benefit. However, these benefits can only appear if governments
and local communities work together to come up with new ways of
ensuring well-managed reserves that can protect marine resources.
</P>
<P>
Fishers are increasingly advocating full protection of reserves
as a way of ensuring healthy fish stocks and their future
livelihood. In the Florida Keys, commercial fishers recently
worked with recreational fishers, divers and conservationists to
jointly design a new marine reserve that promotes sustainable
fishery management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Unemployment Rate Falls to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in Switzerland
has fallen below two percent for the first time in more than eight
years, Swiss Radio International reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Latest figures released by the Swiss Federal Department of
Economic Affairs show 69,788 people were registered as jobless in
May, down from 75,642 in April.
</P>
<P>
Pascal Couchepin, head of the department, said the figures
represented an important moment for the Swiss economy. The
exceptional figures were partly due to current good economic
conditions, and they were also attributed to the flexibility of
the labor market, stable labor relations and the quality of
training, he added.
</P>
<P>
As to regional figures, the department said on Friday that
unemployment had fallen mostly in the Italian-speaking canton of
Ticino. The jobless rate there fell to 2.7 percent. However,
Geneva still has the highest unemployment rate at 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of job vacancies in Switzerland has risen to 15,724.
</P>
</TEXT>
