<HEADLINE> French Yachtsman Sets Upwind Round-the-world Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- French yachtsman Philippe Monnet
broke by 10 day on Friday the record of non-stop solo round-the-
world sailing against prevailing winds and currents.
</P>
<P>
Monnet, who set sail with his yacht Uunet from the French
Brittany port of Brest on January 9 to sail east to west, crossed
the finishing line off the French coast with a total sailing time
of 151 days, 19 hours and 54 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The previous record was 161 days, 16 hours and 32 minutes, set
seven years ago by Briton Mike Golding.
</P>
<P>
"Sailing round the world against the winds, the currents and
the sea ...is not twice as tough, it is five times, 10 times
tougher," Monnet told RTL radio.
</P>
<P>
When describing the odyssey, Monnet said he narrowly escaped
being caught in the Antarctic ice pack, suffered a bout of malaria,
put out a fire on board and even faced an underwater volcanic
eruption a quarter of a mile away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
