<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights of
cultural news stories Xinhua released from June 3 to June 8:
</P>
<P>
-- China to Hold Harbin Summer Concert and National Vocal
Contest
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Culture plans to add a national vocal
competition to the agenda of the 25th summer concert in Harbin,
northeast Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
China Harbin Summer Concert, from August 6 to 15, features 44
performances, including a concert by the China Symphony Orchestra,
a concert by the Central Opera Theater, and famous ballet scenes
performed by the Central Ballet Troupe.
</P>
<P>
The vocal contest, with participants from across the country,
will be held during the course of the 10-day concert series, the
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
-- Ningxia Opens New Relics Museum
</P>
<P>
A new state-level cultural relics museum recently opened in
Guyuan County, northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The 3,000-square-meter museum is home to 11,000 relics,
including three state treasures and 117 state-level cultural
relics. These items combined account for more than 50 percent of
the region's total collection of precious historical pieces.
</P>
<P>
This museum was originally a provincial museum for relics of
the Tibetan nationality.
</P>
<P>
-- Danish Exhibition on Modern Design Opens
</P>
<P>
An exhibition on modern Danish design and architecture opened
on June 7 at the Museum of the Chinese Revolution in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"The Danish Wave" Exhibition shows outstanding architectural
designs and industrial products reflecting both traditional
culture and innovations of the Danish people.
</P>
<P>
Chinese visitors will have opportunities to see the state-of-
the-art designs, said Chinese Vice-Minister of Culture Pan
Zhenzhou.
</P>
</TEXT>
