<HEADLINE> Egypt, Romania Agree on Cooperation in Trade, Investments, Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The first session of the Egyptian-
Romanian Joint Committee has resulted in the signing of several
cooperation agreements, said a senior Egyptian official Friday.
</P>
<P>
The accords deal with a number of aspects of the Egyptian-
Romanian relations, especially in the fields of trade, investment,
industry and transfer of technology, Minister of State for Planning
and International Cooperation Ahmed el-Darsh said.
</P>
<P>
Darsh was speaking to the Cairo-based Voice of Arab radio in a
telephone interview from Bucharest, capital of Romania, before
wrapping up a three-day visit, during which he led the Egyptian
delegation to the committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have agreed to seek the establishment of a
joint venture in Egypt to manufacture bulldozers with Romanian
technology, and exports of bulldozers to other Arab countries, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the two sides followed up trade exchange and
agreed on the necessity to promote Egyptian exports to Romania to
strike a trade balance.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume stood at 227 million U.S. dollars in 1999
between Egypt and Romania. The two sides have agreed to join
efforts to increase trade to one billion dollars in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Romania have also decided to seek ways of expanding
the cooperation efforts to the fields of tourism, oil and gas,
according to the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
