<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches New Loan Scheme for SMEs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Friday introduced an
enterprise program specially designed to resolve the non-
performing loan (NPL) problems of small and medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs)expeditiously.
</P>
<P>
The program, which would take immediate effect, is part of the
government's initiative to support the development of SMEs, Bank
Negara Malaysia (BNM) said in a statement issued here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, new loans worth about 715 million ringgit (
188.157 million U.S. dollars) would be made available by banking
institutions, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the program, it said, SMEs must have been
affected by the financial crisis and their non-performing loans
must be between 500,000 ringgit (131,578 dollars) and 5 million
ringgit (1.315 million dollars) in one banking institution or the
banking system in aggregate.
</P>
<P>
The loans of the affected SMEs should have been classified as
non-performing between January 1, 1998, and April 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed at assisting borrowers who have credit
facilities with a number of banking institutions, using simple and
standard loan restructuring guidelines to accelerate the debt
restructuring process of SMEs, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The program also complements the various mechanisms that have
already been put in place so far to assist SMEs affected by the
financial crisis, including the establishment of a rehabilitation
fund for small and medium industries (SMIs), loan rehabilitation
units at individual banking institutions and the loans complaint
and monitoring unit at BNM.
</P>
<P>
The move would facilitate consensus on restructuring loans in a
cohesive manner and would provide a mechanism to encourage banking
institutions to give additional financing to these SMEs to enhance
the stability of their business in the long run, it said.
</P>
<P>
BNM stressed that all new financing can only be used for
business-related purposes while inter-company transactions would
not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate and expedite the debt restructuring process, BNM
and the banking industry have formulated a set of standard and
simple loan restructuring guidelines which specify the maximum
standstill period, the moratorium on interest payments and the
maximum tenure of the old and new financing.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the program would have to attend compulsory
training to better manage their businesses which will encompass
lessons on cash flow management, computerized accounting, trade
finance and financing tools throughout this year, the bank said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
