<HEADLINE> Greek Terrorist Group Claims Responsibility for Killing British Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A Greek terrorist group, the "
November 17", Friday claimed responsibility for killing British
defense attache, Brigadier Stephen Saunders.
</P>
<P>
In a 13-page letter sent to the Athens daily Eleftherotypia,
the group said that Saunders, 50, was targeted because he played a
key role in NATO's bombing campaign against Yugoslavia last year.
</P>
<P>
"We decided to execute him because through his post he
participated in the planning of the barbaric act raids against
Yugoslavia and, therefore, is among those responsible for last
year's nazi-style crime and the murder of thousands of civilians,"
the letter, carried by the daily, said.
</P>
<P>
The letter added that the British government's role was "more
provocative than that of the United States during the NATO raids
against Yugoslavia".
</P>
<P>
In the letter, the group admitted that the assassination was
being planned since March.
</P>
<P>
Saunders, who had been in Athens since last May, was shot dead
by two gunmen on a motorcycle Thursday as he was driving alone
from his northern suburban home in Nea Erithrea to the British
embassy in downtown Athens.
</P>
<P>
In the past 25 years, the "November 17" group has killed more
than 20 people, including CIA's station-master in Greece Richard
Welsh in 1975, but none of its members have been arrested so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
