<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Development Forum Expresses Optimism, Caution About Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The 2nd Asia Development Forum
ended its discussions Thursday after its participants expressed
both optimism and caution about the socioeconomic development in
East Asia, which has witnessed serious disparities as a result of
globalization in the distribution of wealth and opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the forum's discussions at a press conference
Thursday, Director of Singapore's Institute of Southeast Asian
Studies Chia Siow Yue said, "There are both optimism and caution"
over the sustainable growth in East Asia in the coming years
although it has taken a strong growth road.
</P>
<P>
Optimism emerged on the back of lessons the region has learned
both from its spectacular growth before the crisis and from its
bitter experiences in the financial crisis that swept the region
in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
One general consensus is that East Asia had achieved
substantive and high-rate growth and now the region is on a strong
recovery path although there is some concern that this fast
recovery may not be sustainable and a lot of things are yet to be
done.
</P>
<P>
The participants were convinced that economic and institutional
reforms have to continue, particularly reforms for good corporate
and state governance, reforms in the banking industry and the
financial sector and corporate reforms.
</P>
<P>
The forum gave the strong message that Asian countries should
continually push forward the reforms which are necessary and
essential for sustainable recovery.
</P>
<P>
Attention was also drawn to the fact that the reforms, which
will involve changing institutions, values and social practices,
will take a very long time, even generations.
</P>
<P>
Another agreement is that the fundamentals and basic strategies
that accounted for East Asian success should remain valid and
should not be set aside in a new environment.
</P>
<P>
At the forum, many policy makers and many in the intellectual
community became more cautious as they noted that some fundamental
problems still remain in Asian economies and more state and
corporate restructuring is needed.
</P>
<P>
There is also a general consensus that Asia in the past gave
emphasis and priority to growth and its refined development
strategy must now pay more attention to and focus on issues of
poverty and social inequality to make sure that those in poverty
will not be marginalized and the development process will meet the
expectations of the government and people.
</P>
<P>
In addition to sustainable growth, what the majority of the
participants were most concerned about was a social balance
between growth and equality, the key issue the region is
confronting in meeting challenges from globalization.
</P>
<P>
Participants stressed that the social balance issue is becoming
more and more important as both the gap between countries and the
domestic inter-persons disparity are widening.
</P>
<P>
They called for more efforts by Asian governments to help those
economies that are left behind and are less equipped to build up
their capacities catch up with well-equipped economies.
</P>
<P>
In view of globalization, the information technology revolution
and the competition the region has to face, the participants also
agreed to put more emphasis on human resources development,
education and training which they say will help economies rapidly
become knowledge-based. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
