<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Team to Assess Economic Recovery in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- An economic team of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) is expected to arrive in
Indonesia on June 12 to assess the progress of the economic
recovery program in the country, a senior official said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The IMF (team) will arrive here on June 12, instead of June 30,
to assess the progress which has been made by the government in
its economic recovery program," Coordinating Minister for Economy,
Finance and Industry Kwik Kian Gie told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing special with the forthcoming arrival of the team. It
just will discuss what next to be done by the government (to boost
the on-going economic program," Kwik added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kwik also said the government has done its best to
make the economic recovery program successful.
</P>
<P>
He noted that during the economic crisis, the country's GDP
grew by minus 13 percent, with an inflation rate of 80 percent and
an interest rate of 60 to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
"But now, the interest rate stands at around 11 percent and we
sometimes undergo inflation and also deflation while our GDP has
been growing," Kwik said.
</P>
<P>
"So I don't really understand if you say that the real sector
has not yet begun to recover," Kwik added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, IMF Managing Director Horst Koehler said he was
optimistic over the country's economic growth and pointed out that
that this year Indonesia's economy would grow by 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Koehler also said Indonesia's economic growth has been coming
back and this is a good and encouraging starting point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
