<HEADLINE> Manila Stresses Effort for Peace in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government reassured
the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) Friday that it
would continue to pursue efforts to bring genuine and lasting
peace to Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in a radio interview
that this should allay concerns raised by the claims of the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) that the government is gearing up
for an all-out war in the south.
</P>
<P>
The government troops and the MILF are clashing in the Mindanao
area. Earlier, the government vowed to diminish the Moro rebel
group's military strength.
</P>
<P>
"We never said we are pursuing an all-out war. We merely
respond to acts of harassment by the MILF. We want all-out peace
in Mindanao and that is very important to us," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Philippines would send a delegation to Kuala
Lumpur, capital of Malaysia, later this month to present the
government's side on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The member states of the OIC, an influential forum of more than
50 Islamic states worldwide, reportedly will meet in Malaysia
later this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
