<HEADLINE> Kenya Faces Worst Crisis: Kenyan President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is facing the worst ever
crisis, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi has said.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks Thursday when addressing
thousands of Kenyans who attended a passing out parade for 1,399
police recruits at the Administration Police Training College
here, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Moi said besides famine, the country is having to deal with
power rationing, water shortage, crime, high employment, falling
export earnings and a slump in tourism.
</P>
<P>
He said his government would form a national committee to
coordinate and monitor the distribution of famine relief food,
which is headed by Uhuru Kenyatta, son of Kenya's first president
the late Mzee Jomo Kenyatta.
</P>
<P>
Moi said he was hopeful the problems would be abated if the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank agree to resume aid to
Kenya at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the president further appealed for local and
international aid to help three million Kenyans who are
absolutely destitute and require emergency food relief and life
saving support, due to the prolonged drought befallen the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
