<HEADLINE> Zanzibar to Seek Foreign Assistance Directly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The semi-autonomous Zanzibar
is allowed to directly seek external aid and loans without going
through the Tanzanian central government, the African newspaper
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Submitting the government's budget proposals for the 2000/2001
fiscal year starting in July to the House of Representatives of
the self-governing region including Zanzibar and Pemba Isles, the
Zanzibari Minister for Finance Amina Salum Ali said the Union
government had accepted that Zanzibar should be free to look for
foreign assistance.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, agreement was recently reached
between the Zanzibar and the Union governments, enabling Zanzibar
to have direct contact with foreign countries or agencies when it
comes to seeking aid.
</P>
<P>
The decision will make it easier for Zanzibar to realize about
1.5 billion Tanzanian shillings (about 1.88 million U.S. dollars)
in aid for the next financial year, which it direly need for
stalled development projects, said Amina.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Zanzibar government has appealed to donors to
reconsider their decision of suspending aid to the Indian Ocean
islands for human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
It called on donors to support Zanzibar's development rather
than sponsoring political seminars that further worsen the
situation in the Isles.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar joined with mainland Tanganyika to form the United
Republic of Tanzania in 1964. But it has its own government and
parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
