<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Between Uganda, Rwanda Continues in Kisangani, Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between Ugandan and
Rwandan troops is going on Friday in Kisangani, the third largest
city of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
"The Rwandan Patriotic Army (RPA) is shelling the positions of
the Uganda People's Defence Forces (UPDF) in Kisangani today, and
the UPDF repulses them," Phinehas Katirima, Ugandan Army
Spokesman, told Xinhua in a telephone interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The RPA said they would observe the cease-fire, but they
haven't," he added.
</P>
<P>
The UPDF and the RPA reached a cease-fire on the mid-night on
June 6. But the cease-fire was not observed so far.
</P>
<P>
The 24-hour unilateral cease-fire by the UPDF, which was
declared on Thursday, will not come into effect until the U.N.
Military Observer team establishes presence on the UPDF's side,
Katirima said.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops started to shell each other in
Kisangani after a UPDF's vehicle was attacked and destroyed Monday
morning. The fighting is the latest following clashes between the
two armies in early May.
</P>
<P>
The two former allies have their troops stationed in Kisangani,
a northeast city of the DRC, where they have backed rival rebel
factions fighting against the DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
