<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Condemns Latest Fighting in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
has strongly condemned clashes between Rwanda and Uganda in the
northeastern Congolese city of Kisangani, Times of Zambia
newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who brokered the Lusaka Peace Accord to end the
conflict in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) last July,
told reporters Thursday that the fighting threatened the planned
deployment of 5,500 U.N. peacekeepers in Africa's third largest
country.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very sad turn of events. The whole thing defies
logic and is a big shame to Africa," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"This fighting is a direct threat to the peace process, a
direct threat to peacekeeping plans and a direct threat to
regional stability," Chiluba added.
</P>
<P>
He called on both countries to end the fighting. "I will be
visiting both countries to see what can be done to end this
fighting. We need to find a permanent solution to the Kisangani
crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he had already spoken by telephone with Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni and Rwanda President Paul Kagame over
the latest clash started on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba made the comments after the head of a U.N. observers'
team trying to broker a ceasefire in Kisangani condemned Rwandan
and Ugandan commanders for destroying the Congolese city and
killing innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
Intense shelling and machine gun fire echoed across the city as
Rwandan and Ugandan troops fought for a forth day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the political committee on Congo held a crucial
meeting in Lusaka on Thursday to discuss the pull-out of foreign
troops from the war- torn central African nation.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting followed the 7th plenary session of the
Joint Military Commission (JMC) held earlier here. Sources said
the political committee would discuss modalities for disengagement
of troops and creation of a buffer zone in readiness for the U.N.
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
The planned deployment of U.N. peacekeeping forces and
observers in the DRC has been hampered by ceasefire violations in
some parts of the vast country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
