<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0820 GMT, June 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW -- Polish Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek Thursday appointed
Economy Minister Janusz Steinhoff as Deputy Prime Minister; he
also named three other officials from the Solidary Election Action
(AWS) as new ministers.
</P>
<P>
The appointment came after Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski's announcement on the same day to remove the Freedom
Union (UW) leader Leszek Balcerowicz and three other UW ministers
from their positions. Those newly-named ministers will replace
their UW predecessors who abandoned talks on saving the 30-month
center-right ruling coalition and announced their withdrawal from
the cabinet last week as finance minister, justice minister and
transport and maritime economic minister. (Poland-Goverment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council decided
Thursday night to renew Iraq's "oil-for-food" program for another
period of six months until December 5, 2000.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution, which was unanimously adopted, the Security
Council allowed Iraq to sell as much oil as it can over this
period, which begins June 9. The Security Council also allowed
Iraq to spend 600 million U.S. dollars in this period for spare
parts and equipment to upgrade its dilapidated oil industry. (UN-
Iraq-Program)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's economy grew 2.4 percent in the January-March
quarter from the previous term for the first upturn in three
quarters, the Economic Planning Agency (EPA) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The quarter-to-quarter growth in gross domestic product (GDP)
translates into an annualized expansion of 10.0 percent, the
agency said in a preliminary report. As a result, Japan's GDP, the
total value of goods and services produced domestically, expanded
a real 0.5 percent in fiscal 1999, which ended March 31. (Japan-
Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer will
head to the Solomons Islands Friday as part of a Commonwealth
mission to try to bring an end to fighting there.
</P>
<P>
"The security situation allowing, the intention is to go today,
" a spokesman for Downer told reporters. Meanwhile, a planned
visit by Downer to Fiji has been called off until at least next
week, the spokesman said. (Australia-Solomons-Mission)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Intense fighting broke out anew Friday between the
Philippine government forces and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) in central Mindanao, Philippine News Agency (PNA) said.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the encounters is in the vicinity of the MILF
camps in Carmen and Pikit, all in North Cotabato Province, the PNA
noted. Fighting is so intense that it spilled over to the Cotabato-
Davao highway in the area, prompting local authorities to close
down the route. (Philippine-Fighting) 
</P>
