<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nikkei Index Closes Below 17,000 in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The benchmark Nikkei index in Tokyo
closed below 17,000 Friday for the first time in a week, as the
weaker-than-expected gross domestic product (GDP) data dampened
market hopes for a robust recovery.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 142.43 points, or 0.84
percent from Thursday's 16,861.91 points, listing the fourth
straight day of decline in this week.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX) which covers
all First Section issues, however, rose 0.64 point or 0.04 percent
to 1,586.81.
</P>
<P>
Before the market opened, Japan's Economic Planning Agency (EPA)
said the country's economy expanded 2.4 percent in the January-
March quarter from the previous three-month period.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Japan's GDP grew a real 0.5 percent in fiscal 1999,
undershooting the government's 0.6 percent growth target.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors had been expected to buy more stocks if
stronger GDP data were released, but such expectations have
receded at present, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 1,104.46 million
shares from Thursday's 712.85 million shares due to special
quotation fixing for settling June index futures and options.
</P>
<P>
Warehousing firms, construction firms and information and
telecommunication issues drew buying, while losers included
brokerage houses, retailers and pharmaceutical firms.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers with 697 to 541, while 165 issues closed unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
