<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Firms Develop Handheld Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese companies are developing
handheld computers to meet the growing market demand, industry
sources say.
</P>
<P>
Liang Shuang, a sales manager with the Hisense Group, said that
her company is working with the Chinese Academy of Sciences to
develop color handheld computers.
</P>
<P>
The company will work to improve battery functions and network
technology for these computers.
</P>
<P>
The new products are expected to be put on the market by the
end of this year, she said, adding that the company has already
been able to manufacture black-and-white handheld computers.
</P>
<P>
Hisense Group, based in Qingdao in east China's Shandong
Province, is the eighth biggest electronic enterprise in the
country, mainly producing TV sets, computers, air conditioners,
telephone sets and cameras.
</P>
<P>
The Founder Group Corp., China's computer giant, is working to
further improve the functions of its handheld computers, so that
users can have an easy access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Despite technical problems, all the developers expressed their
beliefs that the handheld computers have a considerable market
potential, because it is easy to take and convenient to use.
</P>
<P>
Other developers of handheld computers include the Langchao
Group based in Jinan of Shandong, Huajian Group affiliated with
the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the Legend Group, and Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
Major Chinese computer companies displayed their handheld
computers at a recent national exhibition on technological
innovation achievements in Suzhou in the eastern Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The companies said that handheld computers are priced at more
than 5,000 yuan (about 600 U.S. dollars), which is deemed too high
for common customers.
</P>
<P>
"If the price is less than 3,000 yuan (about 360 U.S. dollars),
I think the sales will be brisk," said Liu Yonggui, a marketing
manager with Huajian.
</P>
<P>
Foreign handheld computers, such as IBM and Philips, have also
entered China's market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
