<HEADLINE> Evacuation From Solomons Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of foreign nationals
including Australians and New Zealanders have spent the night on
the Australian Navy transport ship the HMAS Tobruk, as they
prepare to evacuate from the strife-torn Honiara, capital of the
Solomon Islands,Television New Zealand reported here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The evacuation comes five days after rebels of the Malaitan
Eagle Force put the prime minister, Bartholomew Ulufa'alu, under
house arrest in a bid to force his resignation. Violent clashes
have been reported around the islands since then.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-two New Zealanders including 14 children were among the
337 people who spent the night on board the HMAS Tobruk, with
another 70 Australians and New Zealanders set to join them Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tobruk can accommodate up to 800 people. It is unclear when the
ship will leave Honiara. The New Zealand Navy frigate Te Mana is
due to arrive there Saturday to continue the evacuation. 
</P>
