<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Weakens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Leading commercial bank in the capital Nairobi Thursday quoted
the shilling at 77.85/78.05 to the dollar from 77.75/77.95 at
Wednesday's close. The previous lowest of the shilling against
the dollar was 77.80 last September.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the shilling fell after investor rushed to close
forward positions in reaction to an appeal from Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi on Wednesday for some 150 million U.S. dollars in
food aid to fight drought.
</P>
<P>
"It looks like the government may have to borrow the money,"
said Stephen Okoko, a dealer with Standard Chartered Bank.
</P>
<P>
The shilling has been under pressure this week after the
government announced a tighter power rationing that gives
industry electricity for just eight hours a day.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here predicted the shilling could weaken in the next
few sessions, although not at such an alarming rate, as power
rationing continued to weigh on the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Majority Ugandans to Vote for Movement System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A national public opinion poll in
Uganda has revealed that 60.8 percent of the voters will vote for
the Movement system in the June 29 referendum on political
systems, while only 23.5 percent of the respondents said they
would vote for the multi-party system, the New Vision reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, which was conducted by K2-Research, a new independent
research firm, during the period of May 25-31, indicated that
while the Movement commands majority support throughout the
country, most of its supporters want it to become a political
party.
</P>
<P>
The Movement led by President Yoweri Museveni regards itself a
non- political party, saying it is a "non-political-party"
politics.
</P>
<P>
Since April this year, the Movement has been involved in
country-wide campaigns.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release by the Research, 67.7 percent of
the respondents thought the Movement would win the referendum
while 11.1 percent said the multipartyists would win.
</P>
<P>
The poll involved 650 adult respondents drawn in proportions
similar to the weights of the northern, central, western and
eastern regions in the national population.
</P>
<P>
Some 69.5 percent of the respondents supported the referendum,
18.2 percent were opposed to it while 10.4 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
About 75.5 percent of the respondents said they would vote in
the referendum, while 23.2 percent said they would not vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Likely to Resume Aid to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) may resume aid to Kenya by the end of this month, the East
African Standard reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi as saying
that senior management and executive boards of both the IMF and
the World Bank had agreed to meet at the end of this month in
stead of July as earlier indicated.
</P>
<P>
Moi, who renewed an appeal for international food aid to help
feed millions of starving Kenyans in rural areas on Wednesday,
said members of international community were sympathetic to
Kenya's economic difficulties following the prolonged drought.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks when he presided over a passing
out parade for 1,399 police recruits in the capital Nairobi
Thursday, but he did not give any details regarding the latest
development on the proposed resumption of aid to Kenya by the two
international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and the World Bank that have been negotiating with the
Kenyan government over resumption of aid for the past three years
gave a nod last month following the latest round of talks in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
However, the agreement reached during last month's talks would
still be subject to ratification by the IMF board in July.
</P>
<P>
According to Kenyan Finance Minister Chris Okemo, Kenya
expected the IMF management board to consider a facility of about
210 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended a loan of 205 million dollars to Kenya in
July 1997 for poor governance and rampant corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
