<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tide in South China Sea Disappears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A red tide that occurred in the
South China Sea off Nan'ao County, in Guangdong Province, on June
7 has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The State Oceanic Administration sent a special team of workers
to Nan'ao to inspect the situation. Planes were used to monitor
the development of the red tide.
</P>
<P>
The red tide did not caused much negative impact to offshore
aquaculture in Nan'ao, one of the major aquaculture bases in
Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
However, experts with the South China Sea Branch of the State
Oceanic Administration have requested relevant departments to keep
an eye for possible red tides returning in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Chinese archeologists believe Persian-style silver basins,
ivory, glass bowls and crystal-bead strings unearthed from a leud
tomb dating back to the Warring States Period (475 BC-221 BC) in
south China's Guangzhou City, suggested China's marine trade with
the Middle and West Asia began much earlier than that through the
ancient "Land Silk Road".
</P>
<P>
The "imported commodities" came to China in the third century
Before Christ. However, the ancient "Silk Road" that starts from
Xi'an City in western China was explored some 200 years later in
119 BC, said Chinese historians.
</P>
<P>
-- The China Securities Regulatory Commission has approved
three investment funds launched in the early 1990s to merge into a
new securities investment fund known as Fund Hanbo upon approval
of their holders.
</P>
<P>
The funds are the Tongfa Investment Fund in northeast Shenyang
city, the Zibo Township Enterprises Investment Fund, both listed
on the Shanghai Stock Exchange, and the Three Gorges Investment
Fund in southwest China's Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
-- Representatives from more than 50 world-famous venture
capital firms, including Morgan Stanley and the International
Digital, have gathered China Internet Venture 2000 to gain a
better foothold in China's Internet development.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet in China is still in its primary stage, and we
expect it to have great potential. And the talent and market here
are also attractive to us," said Michelle Wu, President and CEO of
China Internet Group, Inc.
</P>
<P>
E-commerce business volume is estimated to be 800 million yuan
by the end of this year, and will reach 10 billion by 2002.
</P>
<P>
-- China has succeeded in clearing away the landmines within
its territory after two campaigns of minesweeping.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the campaigns half a year ago, no human and
animal death or injury has been reported from the south and
southwest border areas, where a lot of mines and other explosives
had been left due to past border clashes.
</P>
<P>
The two campaigns have ridded the areas of 1.88 million
landmines and 320,000 pieces of other explosives. A total of 60,
000 hectares of farming land and forests have been reclaimed in
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and Yunnan Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
