<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Industry Maintains Robust Growth in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial production
maintained a robust growth in May, according to the National
Bureau of Statistics (NBS).
</P>
<P>
According to NBS figures, the country's industrial sector
realized 196.3 billion yuan in industrial added-value, rising 11.5
percent over May last year, a growth roughly equivalent to that of
April this year.
</P>
<P>
The sector recorded 890.4 billion yuan in added-value in the
first five months, up 11 percent from the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises realized 115.8 billion yuan in
industrial added-value in May, up 10.6 percent from the same month
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Growth rates for joint stock companies and overseas-funded
businesses were up 14.5 percent and 14.8 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The heavy industrial sector experienced a growth of 12.9
percent in May, which was 0.8 percent higher than in April. Major
heavy industrial products such as steel, cement, electricity and
metallurgical products reported strong growth between 13 to 18
percent over May last year.
</P>
<P>
The light industry realized 78.2 billion yuan in added-value,
representing a growth of 9.6 percent. Light industrial products
such as colored TV sets, air conditioners and refrigerators
witnessed a growth of between 29 to 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales of industrial products rose 0.79 percent in May reaching
97.31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Strong growth in the export of industrial products is an
important factor behind the robust growth in the industry sector,
said NBS.
</P>
<P>
China's industrial enterprises earned 114 billion yuan of
export products in May, an increase of 22.7 percent over May 1999.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate for delivered export products in the first five
months was 26.9 percent, adding 2.9 percent to industrial growth
in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
