<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Veterans to Stay on White-Owned Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Thursday launched his countrywide election campaign tour with a
stern message that the government will not drive out war veterans
from the white-owned farms they occupied until the land issue was
resolved.
</P>
<P>
"We will not drive them out of the farms until the land issue
is resolved and resolved amicably," Mugabe told 12,000 supporters
at a campaign rally in Gutu of southern Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He praised the war veterans for their stance on the land issue,
saying, " they were the vanguard of this phase of the land
revolution."
</P>
<P>
The war veterans have occupied more than 1,000 white-owned
farms since February this year.
</P>
<P>
There had been speculation that the former freedom fighters
would be removed from the farms following the amendment of the
Land Acquisition Act, which now allows the government to acquire
white-owned commercial farms without paying any compensation.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the death of white commercial farmers in
skirmishes with the war veterans, Mugabe said the liberation
fighters were provoked by those whites who resisted, at times, by
using gunfire.
</P>
<P>
He added the British government is making futile attempts to
block the smooth flow of fuel into Zimbabwe in an act of sabotage
meant to discredit his ruling party and bring the government to
its knees.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe will hold the fifth parliamentary elections on June 24
and 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nordic Countries Urge International Aid to African Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Nordic countries will take
positive actions to urge the international community to help
African nations with their social and economic development, said
Danish Prime Minster Poul Rasmussen Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The international community must take concrete measures to
support the social and economic development of the developing
countries, said Rasmussen at a news conference after the one-day
summit meeting Thursday between Nordic countries and South Africa
in Skagen, northern Denmark.
</P>
<P>
The measures included providing financial aids through long-
term loans and direct investment to developing countries, giving
them access to markets and technology, and reducing their heavy
debts, Rasmussen said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Nordic countries also expressed their
support for the call by South African President Thabo Mbeki to
reconstruct Africa. Mbeki, who is in Denmark for a two-day visit
starting Wednesday, left here for home Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
