<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Commonly Used for College Selection in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A national survey released
Thursday reveals that the Internet is now one of the most
pervasive and powerful elements in college selection and
application process among college-bound American high school
students.
</P>
<P>
Results from the survey conducted by the Art &AMP; Science Group,
one of America's market research and consulting firms specializing
in higher education, indicate that the Internet is now both a
widely-favored medium by students for filing an application and a
key source of information as application decisions are made.
</P>
<P>
"The emergence of the Internet, Web sites, online applications
and other new forms of communications technology in college
admission marks one of the most profound changes in the college
selection process in history," the research firm said.
</P>
<P>
Forty-three percent of the 500 students interviewed said that
if they had a choice, they would prefer to file their college
applications via the Internet, while 44 percent indicated that
they preferred the traditional pencil and paper and "snail mail"
method. In actual usage of online application, 35 percent of
respondents reported they used an online application for at least
one of their applications.
</P>
<P>
Respondents ranked the Web second in importance only to
guidance counselors as a key source of information in helping them
decide where to apply for colleges. In fact, 48 percent mentioned
a high school guidance counselor, followed by 37 percent who cited
Web sites with information about colleges. Traditional sources of
information such as friends and college viewbooks trailed far
behind.
</P>
<P>
The Art &AMP; Science Group said that the findings presage greater
changes resulting from the impact of technology on the higher
education market, including the diminishing use of expensive
viewbooks and other printed materials in college selection, new
roles for guidance counselors, and the promise of new
possibilities and efficiencies in enrollment data collection and
management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
