<HEADLINE> Thai Industry Sector Robust But NPLs Hamper Growth: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Suwat was quoted as saying that the industry sector has shown
positive signs as witnessed by the four-month report ending April
that showed industrial production index rose by 12 percent year-on-
year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, industrial production exports in the period amounted
to 22 billion US dollars and are expected to reach 63 billion
dollars by year-end, up 25 percent from the same period a year
earlier, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Thailand had come only half way on the path
to economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
"Stable trade surpluses and steadfast exports are the main
signs of economic improvement," he said, "but when factored with
the risk of the failure of the banking system and mountainous
external debt,recovery was retarded."
</P>
<P>
"Thailand's sovereign debt has skyrocketed to 83 billion
dollars while non-performing loans (NPLs) in the entire banking
system are 38 percent which is alarmingly high. Bank lending,
meanwhile, has contracted in the past four months," Suwat said,
considering these factors as the main hindrance to the economy.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the government turn its attention to the industry
sector as it is the only sector that can bail out the country from
the economic slump. 
</P>
