<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's GDP Grows 2.4 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Japan's economy grew 2.4 percent in
the January-March quarter from the previous term for the first
upturn in three quarters, the Economic Planning Agency (EPA) said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The quarter-to-quarter growth in gross domestic product (GDP)
translates into an annualized expansion of 10.0 percent, the
agency said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Japan's GDP, the total value of goods and services
produced domestically, expanded a real 0.5 percent in fiscal 1999,
which ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
The 0.5 percent GDP expansion undershot the Japanese
government's 0.6 percent growth target, but was the first increase
in three fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
For the January-March quarter, domestic demand and external
demand contributed 1.5 percent and 0.9 percent respectively to the
GDP figure, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Personal spending, which makes up about 60 percent of Japan's
GDP, increased 1.8 percent from the previous quarter, up for the
first time in three quarters.
</P>
<P>
Corporate capital spending grew 4.2 percent, while housing
investment rose 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the reporting quarter, Japan's GDP totaled 486 trillion yen
(4.54 trillion dollars) in annualized terms, compared with 475
trillion yen (4.44 trillion dollars) in the previous period.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports grew by 5.4 percent but imports shrank by 0.6
percent during the three months.
</P>
<P>
"In broad terms, the economy has been recovering steadily. But
it has not crept out of its severe situation entirely," EPA chief
Taichi Sakaiya told a press conference following the release of
the GDP data.
</P>
<P>
Sakaiya said it is premature to say whether the government
needs to compile a supplementary budget for fiscal 2000, adding
that the time is also not ripe for the Bank of Japan to reverse
its hyper-easy monetary policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
