<HEADLINE> Euro 2000 Referees Ordered to Show No Tolerance toward Foul Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- UEFA chief executive Gerhard
Aigner said that referees have been ordered to show no tolerance
toward foul play during the three-week Euro 2000 tournament.
</P>
<P>
Aigner said: "We hope to improve the performance of referees.
We want them to show the quality that they have demonstrated in
European competition this season." "Above all we hope that
referees will take a firm line. We don't want matches to
degenerate."
</P>
<P>
Among other priorities set out by UEFA, referees will be
instructed to clearly step out ten meters to force players to
retreat the correct distance. Referees have also been told to
clamp down on shirt-pulling.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Gamal Ghandour, the only non-European referee, will
officiate Spain's clash with Norway.
</P>
<P>
Ghandour's appointment follows the nomination of a European
referee for a match at this year's African Nations Cup.
</P>
<P>
"The players will be different but I will approach the match in
exactly the same way," Ghandour said. "European and African
football are becoming more alike because so many Africans play in
Europe." 
</P>
</TEXT>
