<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Malaysia for Fair, Open, Transparent Multilateral Trading System (1) (by Wu Dingbao) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The preservation of such a multilateral trading system is
imperative for Malaysia's continued economic prosperity, Kerk Choo
Ting said in a recent exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In pursuing liberalization initiatives, it is important to
ensure the results are mutually beneficial to all, Kerk said,
adding Malaysia will continue to emphasize the principle of
progressive liberalization and recognition of the different
capacities of economies to embrace liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The element of special and differential treatment is to remain
an integral part of the WTO negotiations, he stressed, adding "
Weaker members must not be expected to assume the same level of
commitments to liberalize their markets as the stronger ones."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has assumed and will continue to assume a proactive
role in the WTO negotiations to ensure that the WTO's work program
and agenda takes into account Malaysia's interests and concerns.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will continue to work with other WTO members who share
a common interest or concern, in particular, developing countries
in the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia looks forward to working closely with China in
influencing the WTO' agenda," the deputy minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in line with the WTO obligations, Malaysia, which
joined the GATT (now WTO) in 1957, has increased tariff bindings
up to 65 percent and undertaken tariff reduction on industrial and
agricultural products since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Referring to how Malaysia protects the sectors affected by
liberalization such as car making, telecommunications, finance and
insurance, Kerk said several of these sectors are strategic
industries and as such Malaysia undertakes liberalization
progressively commensurating with their level of development.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia applies the flexibilities provided for under the WTO
which safeguard the domestic industry, he said, adding in the case
of cars, Malaysia has excluded them from its concessions during
the Uruguay Round and the country is able to maintain the existing
tariffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
