<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Tennis Body Launches New Programs for Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- In a campaign to discover young
tennis talent, the Indonesian Tennis Association (Pelti) has
decided to step up efforts to introduce tennis to children.
</P>
<P>
Pelti official in charge of tennis development, promotion and
foreign affairs Martina Widjaja said Indonesia's lack of recent
pride-provoking international achievements were mostly due to the
country's failure to promote new players.
</P>
<P>
The program, known as Mini Tennis, is expected to start in
early July.
</P>
<P>
As part of the nationwide tennis campaign, the association will
also hold tennis contests for Junior and Senior High School
students.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to introduce two programs. The first is a Mini
Tennis Program, which is aimed at elementary school students while
the second involves contests for junior and senior high school
students," Martina was quoted by the Indonesian Observer Friday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
She said the Mini Tennis program, which allows only children
under nine years of age to participate, will require much in the
way of adjustments to Pelti rulings if children are to be
comfortable while playing.
</P>
<P>
"Considering the potential difficulties the children will face
using normal equipment, the International Tennis Federation will
provide the balls and the rackets in mini sizes. We will also
reduce the size of the court," she said.
</P>
<P>
The International Tennis Federation has launched the Mini
Tennis Program worldwide. Hundreds of schools in Europe have
participated in the program.
</P>
<P>
Martina said that the two programs will be tested first in
Jakarta and the Central Java town of Ambarawa in July. She expects
the program to have covered Java by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Other islands will follow suit next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
