<HEADLINE> Australia's Wilson Wins First Stage in Challenge Cycling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Australian Anna Wilson emerged
from a group of 10 riders in the final sprint Thursday and took
the opening stage for the third successive year at the Women's
Challenge cycling race on a rainy, overcast day.
</P>
<P>
Wilson, the road race and time trial silver medalist at last
year's world championships, won the 111-kilometer Boise to Idaho
City stage race by clocking two hours, 46 minutes and 16 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Diana Ziliute of Lithuania and Ina-Yoko Teutenberg of Germany
finished second and third, respectively, in the same time as the
winner -- as did the rest of the top 10.
</P>
<P>
A heavy, though brief, rain fell just after start of the
beginning of the 17th annual race, the world's most lucrative
women's cycling event.
</P>
<P>
The wet roads and strong winds caused three cyclists to crash
early in the race on a sharp left turn. But the participants later
returned to the peloton.
</P>
<P>
The 1,007-kilometer stage race is a key final Olympic selection
event for several of the more than the dozen countries represented.
</P>
<P>
The 11-day race continues through June 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
