<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian FM to Head to Solomons, Fiji Visit off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer will head to the Solomons Islands Friday as part
of a Commonwealth mission to try to bring an end to fighting there.
</P>
<P>
"The security situation allowing, the intention is to go today,
" a spokesman for Downer told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a planned visit by Downer to Fiji has been called
off until at least next week, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Downer will fly to the Solomons with New Zealand Foreign
Minister Phil Goff, the Botswanan foreign minister and a special
representative of the Malaysian prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"They're going to send a message from the Commonwealth," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"They're going to meet with government and other
representatives to convey the Commonwealth's position and they
will also try and talk to the warring parties," he said.
</P>
<P>
The visit plan was only finalized late Thursday night after it
earlier appeared to be in doubt because of continuing fighting in
the Solomons.
</P>
<P>
However, a truce between warring ethnic groups appears to be
holding.
</P>
<P>
On Fiji, the spokesman said "the Fijians didn't really want the
delegation until they had resolved the hostage crisis."
</P>
<P>
Australian Defense Minister John Moore also said on Friday that
he believed the situation in the Solomons was stable enough to
allow the Commonwealth mission to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
"The truce is still holding, and I think that's very hopeful
for the Commonwealth mission," he told the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation radio.
</P>
<P>
"If those people can get there, which includes Foreign Minister
Downer, then we may be able to negotiate some political settlement,
because that's what must happen in the end," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moore said Australia would await the outcome of the talks
before considering whether any peacekeeping force was needed in
the Solomons.
</P>
<P>
"When they report back from those talks, then the government
will consider its next move," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Within defense of course you always have plans, but it's a
long gap, long step, between plans and putting those into action,"
Moore said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
