<HEADLINE> Cyprus Talks Must Get into Substance: British Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- British special envoy for Cyprus,
Sir David Hannay, said here Friday the negotiations on Cyprus must
address the core issues if there is to be any hope of success.
</P>
<P>
Concluding his talks in Cyprus, Hannay told reporters that "we
certainly hope for early decisive progress and that is what we will
be working for in the weeks" ahead of the July Geneva talks.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, which has been mediating between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot communities for a settlement of the divided
island, identified security, constitution, property and territory
as the core issues.
</P>
<P>
But so far the two rival sides have only outlined their
positions during two rounds of proximity talks under the U.N.
auspices, substantive negotiations on those issue are yet to begin.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey invaded and
occupied the northern third of the island after a failed pro-Greece
coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Hannay, the first of several foreign envoys to visit Cyprus to
prepare the ground for the third round of U.N.-sponsored talks
between the two communities on July 5 in Geneva, arrived here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He had met with Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash as well as other officials.
</P>
<P>
Hannay said the background against which foreign envoys are
working has become a lot more favorable, because of the improvement
of relations between Greece and Turkey, which have enormous
influence on the two communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
He urged the two sides to change gear by getting into "the
substance of the core issues" and moving away from "simple
recitation of the individual positions to the U.N.."
</P>
<P>
"The change of gear we are looking for is for the negotiators,
the two sides and the U.N., to get stuck in to the substance of the
core issues and to begin the serious search for solutions," Hannay
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
