<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: King's Visit Consolidates Jordan-U.S. Ties by Wang Bingfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
returned home Friday after a 10-day trip to the United States,
which was widely seen here as a landmark visit that has further
consolidated the strategic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The king said he was satisfied with the results of his extensive
talks in Washington with President Bill Clinton and senior U.S.
political and business figures on bilateral ties, economic
cooperation and developments of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
One of the most visible fruits of the visit is that Washington
promised some 475 million U.S. dollars in various economic and
military aid to the kingdom in fiscal year 2000, almost 100 million
dollars more than 1999. Jordan is the largest recipient of U.S. aid
on per capita basis.
</P>
<P>
Out of different strategic considerations, Jordan and the U.S.
have been moving closer to each other in recent years, and analysts
believe the king's U.S. visit gave this trend a great push.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is in desperate need of economic and military assistance
from Washington, its biggest donor, to lift its economy out of a
decade-old stagnation and to embark on a road of sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
It also wants to uplift its own status on the international
arena through cooperation with the U.S, particularly in the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Washington, on the other hand, takes Jordan as an important ally
in the Arab world and a peace broker between Israel and its Arab
neighbors, and as a bridge of dialog between Arab countries and the
U.S. itself.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, becoming the
second Arab country after Egypt to strike peace with the Jewish
state.
</P>
<P>
During his U.S. trip, King Abdullah promised to make continued
efforts for progress in Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and a
resumption of the Israeli-Syrian track, stalled since January due
to Israel's refusal to promise full return of the Golan Heights it
seized from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
The king also pledged to work towards a just, durable and
comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Clinton pledged his continuous support for the
king's efforts to improve Jordan's economic performance and to push
the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
The 36-year-old Jordanian monarch also scored in bilateral trade
and economic cooperation with the U.S.. He signed with Clinton an
agreement on jointly establishing a free trade zone and on U.S.
help to build Jordan's information technology industry.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been eyeing for a larger share in the American market
since it joined the World Trade Organization late last year, and it
is counting on the envisaged free trade zone to create more jobs to
check its growing unemployment, which stands at over 14 percent
according to official statistics, if not 27 percent by independent
estimates.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade is gaining increased importance in bilateral
ties since the two countries signed in 1997 an agreement on the
economic and social security of Jordan. The trade volume hiked to
1.29 billion dollars in 1999 from a meagre 7.77 million dollars in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Prime Minister Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh said the king's
just-concluded visit to the U.S. would further bolster bilateral
trade opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
