<HEADLINE> Second Salvo of Sun Plasma to Hit Earth: Canadian Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Canadian scientists are warning of
the arrival of the second salvo of sun plasma Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Geomagnetic Forecasting Center posted a "major
storm warning" for both Thursday and Friday, but said the second
solar salvo appears weaker than the first hitting the earth's
magnetic field Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Canadian scientists said they expect a weaker solar salvo
judging by its estimated speed and the size of the radiation burst
or solar flare that accompanied it.
</P>
<P>
No serious technical problems have been reported in Canada
since the massive solar storm first hit earth at about 5 a.m.
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the high Arctic, however, the blast made radios useless
Thursday with some camps operated by the Canadian Geomagnetic
Forecasting Center being caught in a blackout, the center
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
But the disturbance seemed only about half as bad as in 1989,
when the solar storm last hit earth, leaving 6 million Canadians
without power for hours in winter, according to Canadian
scientists.
</P>
<P>
Such havoc is caused when charged particles from the sun hit
the earth every 11 years to distort the magnetic field and
generate power surges in transmission systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alitalia Takes Tough Line With Ex-Partner KLM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Italian national carrier Alitalia won'
t be giving back the 100 million euros (about 102 million U.S.
dollars) which KLM Royal Dutch Airlines invested in Milan's new
airport Malpensa 2000, and is planning to sue its former strategic
partner for 250 million euros in damages, according to a company
statement issued Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, released ahead of a shareholders' meeting next
Friday, said that the Italian airline "viewed the justifications
given by KLM for breaking its alliance accord as insufficient and
incongruous and believes it has no grounds for claiming back its
contribution of 100 million euros."
</P>
<P>
It also said that Alitalia "reserves the right to sue for
damages incurred by KLM's illegitimate withdrawal from the
alliance" to the tune of 250 million euros.
</P>
<P>
It said that, if it failed to reach an out-of-court agreement
with KLM, then it would take its case to Amsterdam, where it would
be heard by a panel of three judges, one Italian, one Dutch and
the third belonging to a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch airline made the abrupt announcement on April 28 that
it was withdrawing from its strategic accord with Alitalia, citing
uncertainties surrounding the future of Malpensa and the stalled
privatization of Alitalia, which was originally slated for sell-
off by June 30.
</P>
<P>
It demanded that Alitalia refund the 100 million euros it
forked out on December 30 as its contribution towards the costs of
upgrading the troubled hub of Malpensa, originally a small
military airport.
</P>
<P>
The development of Malpensa into a fully operational
international hub was a crucial feature of the alliance announced
by KLM and Alitalia in December 1997 and which became operative in
November 1999, with KLM retaining the option of terminating the
accord if the airport failed to take off.
</P>
<P>
Malpensa has been dogged by problems ever since its official
launch in the autumn of 1998, with environmental concerns,
stemming from unacceptable noise pollution levels, playing a major
part in its failure to become fully operational.
</P>
<P>
Friday's statement also said that cost-cutting would be
Alitalia's main aim this year, through measures which would not,
however, interfere with its development strategy.
</P>
<P>
It said that it would be eliminating all non-essential, short-
term investment projects.
</P>
<P>
It said that it would not be hiring any new staff in 2000 and
that its current work-force would be reduced by 1,000.
</P>
<P>
Before KLM decided to dump Alitalia, the two carriers were
debating a full merger, and just at the beginning of April,
Alitalia, KLM, KLM's long-time partner Northwest and Continental
announced that a colossal four-way alliance called Wings would
soon be taking off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
