<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Aid Agencies Calls for End to Fighting in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations aid
agencies have called for a halt in the fighting between Rawandan
and Ugandan troops in Kisangani, a town in the Democratic Republic
of Congo (DRC), where the humanitarian situation is deteriorating
rapidly, a U.N. spokesman said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press conference here that
despite an agreement by Rwanda and Uganda to cease fire Thursday,
armed hostilities continued for the fifth straight day in the
northern town of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
Heavy shelling had put a halt to U.N. humanitarian operations
in the town where hundreds of people had been reported dead and
wounded and there was no electricity or running water, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We just spoke with the force commander who says that the U.N.
mission in Kisangani was working on a humanitarian cease-fire so
that urgently needed assistance could be provided to the
populations," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a joint statement issued here, the chiefs of
five U.N. relief agencies Friday expressed "grave concern" about
the plight of civilians in Kisangani, echoing statements made by
the U.N. Security Council and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply dismayed about the situation facing civilians in
Kisangani, especially children and women, many of whom are already
malnourished," said the heads of the World Food Program (WFP), the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), the World
Health Organization (WHO), the U.N. Office for the Coordination of
Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) and the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
"We urge the governments of Rwanda and Uganda to immediately
end the fighting that is killing innocent civilians," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. organizations said that the city's entire civilian
population was under fire and completely cut off from humanitarian
relief. They also underscored their concern about the current
inability of humanitarian organizations to move urgently-needed
relief goods across front lines, and noted that vaccines in cold
storage in Kisangani were being compromised due to the lack of
electricity for refrigeration.
</P>
<P>
The polio immunization campaign slated for July in Kisangani
province -- covering an area the size of France -- was now in
serious jeopardy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
