<HEADLINE> Prince Charles Press Secretary Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Prince of Wales's press
secretary Friday resigned in a row over who owns the valuable
copyright to pictures of Prince William.
</P>
<P>
Sandy Henney, who had been in the job for seven years, tendered
her resignation which was accepted by Charles "with deep regret."
</P>
<P>
She was accused of breaking an agreement with the Daily
Telegraph after releasing photographs to other national newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph and St James's Palace both claimed they
owned the copyright.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the palace said: "The copyright of these
pictures should have been established at the time they were taken
to ensure that St James's Palace owned the copyright and that any
proceeds arising from the use of the photographs went to charity
as has normally happened in the past."
</P>
<P>
"This issue was not resolved and copyright is now wrongly
vested elsewhere. We share our part of the blame in that we should
have taken action to ensure that copyright was vested with us," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph and its royal photographer Ian Jones were
given access to William to take pictures marking his 18th birthday
on June 21. The photos at Eton were to be released to all national
newspapers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
