<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Germany Almost Agree Upon European Institutional Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- French and German leaders Friday
almost reached at their 75th summit in Mainz, western Germany, an
agreement on European institutional reform, the key task of France
during its European Union (EU) presidency in the second half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
French officials said that the summit formally renewed the role
of the French-German locomotive in pushing forward the European
integration, and will pave the way for a successful French EU
presidency.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said after the summit
meeting with President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin that Germany and France have reached understanding without
exception on the issue of EU institutional reform and the details
of the agreement will be worked out by the foreign ministers of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
``We have agreed upon the limit of number of the European
commissioners, and the need to make as quickly as possible the
decisions on the qualified majority in the EU council of ministers,
'' he said.
</P>
<P>
A reform of the EU institutions, above all the voting mechanism
of the EU councils of ministers, will be needed for the
enlargement of EU into a body with from 25 to 30 members in future
instead of the present 15 members.
</P>
<P>
France also seems to have reached a compromise with Germany on
the re-balancing of the number of votes to be shared by each
country in the councils of ministers, which is the main thorny
issue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Germany wants to have more votes because its population is much
bigger than those of France, Britain and Italy, with whom Germany
share the same number of votes at the present time.
</P>
<P>
``Taking into account of the demographical factor is desirable,
'' said Chirac at the joint press conference with Schroeder in the
wake of the summit.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said that Germany and France will find a solution to
the problem by taking into account both the factors of population
and influence of EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
France is opposed to the idea of Germany having more votes than
it does in the council of ministers, because it considers its
political influence no less than Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
