<HEADLINE> Fujimori Inaugurates Andean Countries Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori
inaugurated Friday here the 12th summit of the Andean Community
Nations (ACN).
</P>
<P>
Amid heavy security, presidents Hugo Banzer of Bolivia, Andres
Pastrana of Colombia, Gustavo Noboa of Ecuador and Hugo Chavez of
Venezuela attended the summit's opening ceremony at a hotel here,
along with summit host Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Peruvian state and pro tempore ACN president
Fujimori highlighted during the opening ceremony the strength of
the bloc, and proposed the creation of an Andean nationalism.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori said that the target for the Andean countries in the
21st century will be the full integration in all aspects of the
five countries that form the Community of Andean Nations.
</P>
<P>
Colombian President Andres Pastrana recommended to the Andean
heads of state the building of the Andean unity for the benefit of
the future generations of that regional bloc.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana said that only with a sincere commitment and with a
political will of all and every one of the Andean nations, it will
be possible to arrive at the ambitious goals they have set for
themselves to fulfill a bicentennial dream and for the good of
their citizens.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that while the official agenda of the
summit covers regional stability and economic integration, the
gathering of leaders, which continues through Saturday, may also
afford Fujimori an opportunity to confirm regional recognition for
his government.
</P>
<P>
President Alberto Fujimori won his third term in office in the
May 28 runoff election with 51.6 percent of the vote. His rival,
Alejandro Toledo, who boycotted the poll after complaining of
electoral fraud, garnered about 17.7 percent of the ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
