<HEADLINE> Bush Unveils Government Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Texas Governor George W. Bush of
the United States has unveiled a government reform plan that he
said would save 88 billion dollars over five years.
</P>
<P>
The presumptive Republican presidential candidate Friday
pledged to cut federal bureaucracy by not replacing 40,000 senior
and middle managers scheduled to retire over the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed creating a chief information officer and
spending 100 million dollars on a program to support interagency e-
commerce proposals.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Bush suggested creating a "sunset review board" to
recommend elimination of duplicative jobs, and to make government
more modern by moving all significant government procurement to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"Today when Americans look to Washington, they see a government
which is slow to respond, slow to reform, ignoring changes that
are taking place in the private sector and in some local and state
governments," Bush said in a campaign speech in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
The Texas governor promised to establish a citizen-centered
government that will listen and answer to the people.
</P>
<P>
Bush's proposals invited harsh criticism from the presidential
campaign of Democratic Party candidate Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
Complaining of inconsistencies between Bush's words and stated
intentions, Gore's campaign noted that since Bush took office as
Texas governor in 1995, the two-year Texas budget has grown from
72.8 billion dollars to 98.1 billion dollars, a 36 percent
increase, compared with 21 percent on the federal level.
</P>
<P>
"Governor Bush should try to keep the promises he made to Texas
before making promises to the rest of the country," said Doug
Hattaway, spokesman of Gore's campaign.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
