<HEADLINE> U.S., DPRK Agree to Resume Search for Remains of U.S. Servicemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) agreed Friday to
resume a joint effort to locate and recover the remains of
American servicemen who are unaccounted for from the Korean War, U.
S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after three days of talks in Kuala
Lumpur between representatives of the U.S. Defense Department and
the DPRK's Liberation Army, they said. And the first search
mission is scheduled for June, 25, they added.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the agreement, the United States will be
allowed 20 people on its search teams. Each mission will last 25
days.
</P>
<P>
The last U.S. search for the remains of U.S. servicemen was
conducted in November 1999. 
</P>
