<HEADLINE> Zambian President Condemns Latest Fighting in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
has strongly condemned Rwanda and Uganda for latest fighting in
Kisangani, the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), the Times
of Zambia newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, mediator for peace in the DRC, said here in an
interview on Thursday that the fighting defied logic and
threatened a United Nations plan to deploy peacekeepers in
Africa's third largest country.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very sad turn of events. The whole thing defies
logic and is big shame to Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This fighting is a direct threat to the peace process, a
direct threat to peacekeeping plans and a direct threat to
regional stability," he added.
</P>
<P>
He called on both countries to end the fighting. "I will be
visiting both countries to see what can be done to end this
fighting. We need to find a permanent solution to the Kisangani
crisis," Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, he had already spoken by telephone
with Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Rwanda President Paul
Kagame who is now in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba made the remarks soon after the head of a U.N. team
trying to broker a ceasefire in Kisangani condemned Rwanda and
Uganda commanders for destroying the Congolese city and killing
innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
Intense shelling and machine gun fire echoed across the city as
Rwandan and Ugandan troops fought for the fourth day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the political committee on the DRC held a crucial
meeting in Lusaka on Thursday to discuss the pull-out of foreign
troops from the war- torn central African nation.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting followed the seventh plenary session of
the Joint Military Council (JMC) held earlier here. It is said
that the political committee would discuss modalities for
disengagement of troops and creation of a buffer zone in readiness
for the U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
The planned deployment of more than 5,000 U.N. peacekeepers and
 observers in the DRC has been hampered by ceasefire violations in
some parts of the vast country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
