<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Committee for Congo Ceasefire Adopts Mechanisms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Political Committee for the
implementation of ceasefire in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC) ended its sixth meeting here Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The meeting adopted mechanisms for disarmament, demobilization,
 resettlement and reintegration of members of all armed groups as
stipulated in the Lusaka ceasefire agreement signed by all
belligerents in July and August last year.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the implementation of the Disengagement Plan,
the committee said in an agreement adopted by the two-day meeting
that all the parties had fulfilled their undertaking to submit
information on location of their troops.
</P>
<P>
The committee further noted that the completion of the drawing
up of sub- plans had reached an advanced stage.
</P>
<P>
The committee commended the Joint Military Commission (JMC) for
its work towards the implementation of various aspects of the
Lusaka ceasefire agreement.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was attended by all parties to the ceasefire
 agreement, noted that resource constraints continue to pose a
serious impediment to the speedy discharge of its
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
It appealed to the international community to step up its
support to the JMC so that it can perform its work more
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
On the release of prisoners of war, the agreement said, all the
parties still holding prisoners should declare their readiness to
release them immediately and without pre-conditions.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the inter-Congolese Dialogue, the committee
welcomed the establishment of regular contacts between itself and
the office of the Facilitator of the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also accepted an invitation from the United Nations
Security Council for a consultative meeting in New York on June
15-16, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the political committee expressed concern over the
continued fighting in Kisangani and welcomed the various efforts
being employed to return the situation to normalcy.
</P>
<P>
It urged the parties concerned to immediately put an end to the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
