<DOCNO> XIE20000609.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Founder's Son Named Presidential Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's ruling Chama Cha
Mapinduzi (CCM) party nominated on Friday Zanzibar Minister for
Communications and Transport Amani Abeid Karume as its candidate
for the isles presidency in the October general elections.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the central town of Dodoma said that Karume, 52,
the eldest son of the late founding president of Zanzibar since
the 1964 revolution, Abeid Amani Karume, scooped 111 out of 196
votes cast at a special meeting of the powerful CCM National
Executive Committee (NEC).
</P>
<P>
Karume vowed following the voting that he would defend the
union between Zanzibar and the mainland at any cost and boost the
isles economic development if elected Zanzibar President.
</P>
<P>
CCM Secretary General Philip Mangula told a press conference
that Karume beat three other CCM contenders by winning 56.63
percent of the total votes casting.
</P>
<P>
Karume urged supporters of his rivals, Zanzibar Chief Minister
Mohamed Gharib Bilal, Zanzibar Finance Minister Amina Said Ali and
Union Deputy Minister for Finance Abdisalaam Issa Khatib, to
automatically dissolve after a winner has been chosen.
</P>
<P>
Veteran Ambassador Hassan Ahmed Diria was also on the list of
aspirants but he withdrew his candidature before the NEC day-long
session reportedly to avoid creating groupings within the party.
</P>
<P>
The CCM is a mature political party with a long history of
respecting democracy, Karume said, the nomination outcome would
not create any enmity or division among Zanzibaris.
</P>
<P>
He would face the challenge by the Civic United Front (CUF),
the main opposition party in Zanzibar whose Secretary General Seif
Sharif has vowed to win the October 29 second multiparty elections
in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
When collecting presidency candidate forms on May 6, Karume
said that a ruling party must forge working ties with rival
political parties to achieve development objectives.
</P>
<P>
"Rapid development will only be possible in the Isles when
cooperation of all political parties is achieved," he said.
"Parties are an integral part to democracy."
</P>
<P>
However, he did not say specifically if he would form a
coalition government with the oppositions if elected.
</P>
<P>
The semi-autonomous Zanzibar region in the Indian Ocean joined
with mainland Tanganyika to form the United Republic of Tanzania
after a revolt in 1964 led by the elder Karume that ousted the
sultan and Omani Arabs who ruled the island.
</P>
<P>
The elder Karume led Zanzibar until he was assassinated on
April 7, 1972.
</P>
<P>
A special congress of the CCM is scheduled on Saturday to
confirm CCM Chairman and Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa the
sole candidate for the Union presidency.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement by Tanzania's National Electoral
Commission on Thursday, a total of 12.5 million of the 30 million
population are expected to vote in 232 constituencies throughout
the country in this year's general elections.
</P>
<P>
According to a time table issued by the NEC early this year,
the registration of voters will be conducted between August 1 and
21 while the nomination of contestants will be made on August 13,
and election campaigns between August 14 and October 28.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania had been under a single political party (CCM) system
from 1965 until 1992 when the multiparty system was introduced.
</P>
<P>
The October elections will be the second time since 1995, but
the first time in the country's post-independence history for
presidential, parliamentary and civic elections to be held
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
All the 13 fully registered political parties will run for the
elections which are likely to be dominated by the ruling CCM, at
least on the mainland as President Mkapa, who won the 1995
elections, is expected to win him the second five-year term.
</P>
</TEXT>
