<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Mixed Amid Tame Inflation Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks ended mixed
Friday after a government report showed that the inflation rate in
May rose slightly but remained tame.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 54.66 at 10,614.06.
The blue chip index finished the week with a loss of 180.70 points.
</P>
<P>
But the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 49.28 at 3,
874.84. The composite rose 61.46 points in the week.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index fell 4.72 at 1,456.95.
</P>
<P>
The stocks sensitive to higher interest rates fell after the
Labor Department reported that outside the volatile energy and
food categories, the "core" rate of inflation at the wholesale
level rose 0.2 percent in May, slightly above analysts'
predication. In March and April, core prices rose 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report failed to calm inventors' fears of higher rates,
dragging the Dow and the S&AMP;P lower. The Federal Reserve has raised
rates six times since last June in an effort to cool off the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
But investors moved in the technology sector to buy stocks of
Qualcomm and Sun Microsystems, driving the Nasdaq index higher.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 3.50 at 648.44. But the American Stock
Exchange index rose 1.98 at 939.75 and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 8.52 at 523.06.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,671 up, 1,218 down and 507
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 782.64 million shares from 842.33
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
