<HEADLINE> Brazilian Public Accounts To Fulfill IMF Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Most Brazilian banks, institutes,
federations, and firms expect the country's public accounts to
fulfill the goals agreed on with the International Monetary Fund (
IMF).
</P>
<P>
Local news media said Friday that 63.4 percent of the 97 main
entities of the country polled by the Central Bank in May
presented the expectation that the public accounts of the Union,
the states and municipalities will have this year a primary
surplus of 3.25 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The forecast was brought down, in the average, to 3.1 percent
of the GDP in 2000, and 3 and 2.2 percent in 2001 and 2002,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The study said in relation to foreign trade that there will be
a 2.6 billion U.S. dollar trade surplus this year, 4.4 billion
dollars in 2001, and 5.8 billion dollars in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Those polled also said that they expect direct foreign
investment to amount to 25 billion dollars this year, 21.3 billion
next year, and 20.7 billion dollars in 2002. 
</P>
