<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Swift Completion of Verification in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The verification process has begun with a brief postponement
due to technical problems, and more work will need to be done
Saturday, Annan's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"Verification is the sole responsibility of UNIFIL, but the
task will require the full cooperation of the parties, which the
Secretary-General is confident of receiving," spokesman Fred
Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. teams continued to work with Israeli experts on Israel's
side of the withdrawal line, and other U.N. teams, in tandem with
Lebanese experts, will resume their verification work on the
Lebanese side of the line Saturday, he confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to inform the Security Council in writing
once the UNIFIL force commander, Maj. Seth-Kofi Obeng, reports to
him on the verification teams' work, according to Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and carved up a border strip as
a so-called "security zone" in 1985 to allegedly protect its
northern area from cross-border attacks by Lebanese Muslim
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted resolutions 425 and 426 after
the Israeli invasion, demanding immediate and unconditional
Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state decided earlier this year to pull out from
Lebanon by July 7. However, it completed withdrawal of its troops
from southern Lebanon on May 24.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected its military presence in southern Lebanon,
claiming that some areas along the borderline are still occupied
by Israel and insisting that its deployment in the south will be
done only after the U.N. confirmation of full Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief continued to follow very closely developments on
the ground in Southern Lebanon, believing that the parties have
come a long way: Israel towards complete withdrawal and Lebanon
towards the reassertion of its sovereignty and territorial
integrity, said Eckhard, adding that Annan voiced his wish for the
verification process to be completed as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
