<HEADLINE> U.S., Mexico Sign Gulf of Mexico Boundary Line Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Mexico
signed an agreement Friday for the settling of boundary lines in a
potentially oil-rich area of the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed at the White House by Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and Mexican Foreign Affairs Secretary
Rosario Green, with President Bill Clinton and Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo observing.
</P>
<P>
The agreement now goes to the U.S. Senate for approval.
</P>
<P>
The deal settles the last U.S.-Mexican differences over
territorial waters, giving Mexico almost 61.8 percent of the
underwater area, and the United States the remaining 38.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the agreement, the United States is
prevented from unilaterally awarding contracts to drill for oil
across the area.
</P>
<P>
The American petroleum Institute welcomed the agreement, saying
it gave U.S. companies greater opportunities to explore for oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
