<HEADLINE> Argentine President Criticizes General Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Fernando
de la Rua said Friday that the general strike called by the three
labor centrals is "unnecessary and useless."
</P>
<P>
The president admitted before the local press that the country
faces a very difficult economic situation, especially because of
the big trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the government took "painful" measures to
solve the serious problems of the balance of trade deficit, and
said that this policy aims at the development and growth of the
country with social equality, giving attention to social problems.
</P>
<P>
The president deplored the occurrence of some episodes of
violence and forcefully condemned those actions, and insisted that
no answers or solutions to the problems can be found with violence.
</P>
<P>
Rodolfo Daer of the General Labor Confederation (CGT) Friday
called on the government to get out of its isolation and seek an
agreed-on solution in defense of production and work.
</P>
<P>
Daer told the press that the wide response to the strike is "a
call of attention to the government," and called on it to convoke
to a dialogue to seek an agreement to solve the current situation.
</P>
<P>
The De la Rua government announced on May 19 a package of
measures of adjustment that include a reduction of the salaries of
public servants who earn more than one thousand pesos (the same in
dollars) a month, and the privatization of the workers health
system, which caused strong repercussions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The three national labor union centrals Friday called for a
general strike as a protest against the government's adjustment
measures, which had a big response in the whole country. 
</P>
