<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stocks End In Mixed Picture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Europe's leading stock markets
closed mixed Friday, with traditional economy stocks being the
biggest movers as recently volatile high-tech and telecom sectors
settled down.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index fell 52.8 points, or 0.8 percent, to 6,
443.8 amid weakness in technology, media and telecom sector stocks,
taking the index's loss for the week to 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Leading the list of the decliners was software maker Sage Group,
off 7.9 percent in the wake of a decline for U.S. competitor Great
Plains, which warned of slower-than-expected growth ahead.
</P>
<P>
Energis, the UK's biggest carrier of Internet traffic, fell 7.4
percent, network operator Kingston Communications fell 6.4 percent
and computer services provider Logica dropped 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300 was unchanged at 1,618.82. The tobacco
sector sub-index fell 2 percent while the mining industry
component added 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
German shares made modest gains in thin late trade with benign
U.S. producer data easing rate rise concerns across the Atlantic.
The Xetra Dax index closed up 11.40 or 0.16 percent higher at 7,
254.53 points, down 184.42 from seven days ago.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 rose 25.39 points, or 0.4 percent, to 6,
540.10, with small gains in technology shares outweighing modest
falls in the auto sector. For the week, the index fell 1.9 percent.
